@897  = ~Lask and I are no more than friends now, but I want him back so badly! Help me win him back, Haer'Dalis!~
@898  = ~Aye, he is an attractive man, though I wonder if he is capable of affection for anyone but himself.~
@899  = ~The carrion crow does not seem the sort to do things by halves, my raven. Mayhap you should be more cautious.~
@900  = ~Strange, and stranger yet...~
@901  = ~Your Lask does not seem the sort to respond well to such things, though perhaps that is your hope, aye?~
@902  = ~Ah. I see. Well, that is good to know, I suppose.~
@903  = ~You are a grown woman, free to choose what lovers you will. I assume by the way you ask this question that you wonder if I will cling to jealousy or force you to make a choice or some such?~
@904  = ~You don't seem the possessive type.~
@905  = ~I was trying to be considerate. I didn't want to put you into a situation that would make you uncomfortable.~
@906  = ~It's nothing more than curiosity, really.~
@907  = ~Can you honestly say you *wouldn't* make me choose?~
@908  = ~I really don't know why I brought it up.~
@909  = ~Then you know me well, though I will be perfectly blunt and add that I also do not make a habit of being used for o'erlong by the whims of others. 'Tis a tiring game when one is the toy itself.~
@910  = ~I thank you for the courtesy, but I assure you that 'twas unnecessary. I am not known for withholding my opinions, as you might have gathered by now, and would not hesitate to vocalize my complaints if any were to be found.~
@911  = ~Shall I insert a quaint proverb about cats and their curiosity, hmm?~
@912  = ~Aye. I can honestly say just that.~
@913  = ~No? Well, I shall be here when you remember, hmm?~
@914  = ~While I cannot profess joy at the prospect of seeing you in the arms of another, I also cannot claim any distinct sense of disdain for the idea either. Do what pleases you, my raven.~
@915  = ~Thank you for your understanding, Haer'Dalis.~
@916  = ~Wow. How... refreshing.~
@917  = ~You wouldn't fight for me?~
@918  = ~That's just disgusting! You would really *share* me with someone else?!~
@919  = ~Ah, I do not know if 'understanding' is the correct word, but you are most welcome nonetheless, dearest <CHARNAME>.~
@920  = ~As your reaction leads me to believe you are aware, most other prospective lovers will not share your sparrow's opinion on this. I can be discrete, if that is your wish, but all the discretion in the world is often not enough to blind a man forever.~
@921  = ~Just... keep that in mind, my raven.~
@922  = ~Hah! If there is any woman in the Prime and beyond who does not have need of a champion, it is you, my <CHARNAME>! I would not insult you by presuming, and you oughtn't insult yourself with the implication.~
@923  = ~That is not to say you are not a woman worth fighting for, but in some petty squabble of jealousy and ego? No. Never.~
@924  = ~'Twas you who brought this up, my hound! Now that the truth is known, you are welcome to trade your affection for this sparrow to anyone who might desire it and be done with me.~
@925  = ~I have to wonder why you tell me this. Do you think to provoke jealousy with knowledge that I already possessed? Or mayhap 'tis the opposite? You fear I will become possessive and wish to reassure me that such measures are not necessary?~
@926  = ~I didn't want you to think I was losing interest in you.~
@927  = ~I had to be honest with you. I don't keep things from people who are important to me.~
@928  = ~Maybe I just want you to fight for me.~
@929  = ~Such neglect would likely be obvious to this bard. As much as I appreciate the courtesy, and your continued affections, you need not worry that I require petty reassurances. I am here if you need me, however you need me.~
@930  = ~Honesty is... something I have little enough experience with, in truth. As much as I appreciate the courtesy, and your continued affections, you need not worry that I require petty reassurances. I am here if you need me, however you need me.~
@931  = ~Alas, the heart wants what it wants. If that means your affections have turned away from this sparrow, then so shall it be.~
@932  = ~No, it hasn't turned from you. That's exactly the problem!~
@933  = ~I'm just so confused. I don't know what I want!~
@934  = ~Maybe it's best if we just end it now.~
@935  = ~I want you to fight for me, Haer'Dalis.~
@936  = ~Problem? Why?~
@937  = ~There is little need for you to make a choice at present, my raven. Well, not unless your other significant other forces a confrontation, of course.~
@938  = ~Is that truly what you desire?~
@939  = ~Yes. Let's just be friends, Haer'Dalis.~
@940  = ~No. I care about you.~
@941  = ~Glad I am to hear that. Come, let us dwell upon these thoughts no more.~
@942  = ~The game of envy is a dangerous one, my raven. I do not mind playing a lead role in such tawdry little shows, but mayhap the seeds are already sewn? If your eye wanders my way, your other love will surely take notice.~
@943  = ~Beyond that? I think it is in my best interest to play a passive role and see what comes of all this, aye?~
@944  = ~If the loss has brought you pain, then I am sorry for that, but I admit I am pleased to hear this. I do not count myself a jealous bard, but neither do I wish to share you, my raven. Thank you for telling me.~
@945  = ~And work to reverse what entropy has torn asunder? No, my raven. Not even for you would I attempt such a thing.~
@946  = ~Of course, my raven. What do you wish of me?~
@947  = ~Tell me about Sigil.~
@948  = ~What exactly is a planewalker?~
@949  = ~Will you tell me a little about the Doomguard?~
@950  = ~What is it like to be a tiefling?~
@951  = ~Why did you decide to pursue the life of a bard?~
@952  = ~How old are you?~
@953  = ~What would you say if I asked you to share my bed with me this evening?~
@954  = ~Tell me about your parents.~
@955  = ~Will you tell me about your sister?~
@956  = ~What happened to you in the Blood War?~
@957  = ~Where is your mother now?~
@958  = ~Why did you leave Raelis to join up with me?~
@959  = ~Do you miss Sigil?~
@960  = ~Weren't you supposed to be writing a book or a play or some such about me?~
@961  = ~I need to talk about Yoshimo.~
@962  = ~After all this time, you've finally met Imoen.~
@963  = ~Have you ever heard of someone surviving without a soul?~
@964  = ~You've seen a lot in your life, Haer'Dalis. Have you ever seen anything like the Slayer?~
@965  = ~The Underdark is finally behind us. What did you think of it?~
@966  = ~Those elves certainly weren't the friendliest lot.~
@967  = ~Bodhi is finally dead for good.~
@968  = ~Haer'Dalis... can we win this?~
@969  = ~Never mind. Let's move on.~
@970  = ~Oh, my raven, I fear I could ramble on for ages and eons about my fair home. Have you something specific you wish to know?~
@971  = ~Nothing specific, no. Perhaps you could just tell me something of your experiences there?~
@972  = ~What *is* Sigil?~
@973  = ~What does it look like?~
@974  = ~Who lives there?~
@975  = ~Who's in charge?~
@976  = ~Nevermind. I'm not really interested in Sigil.~
@977  = ~Oh? Such a pity.~
@978  = ~Hmm... It may surprise you, but this sparrow's favorite haunts were not taverns, inns or bordellos - though the Brothel of Slacking Intellectual Lusts was always a delight - but where I found the most joy was in the markets. I frequented the many curiosity shops, always in search of new and wondrous items, or I would simply find a shadowed corner from which to watch the Lady's Handmaidens as they worked, or the petty thugs and harlots weaving into the crowds to ply their skills. Many times I would swap delightful stories with wildly superstitious fishwives or wanderers passing through. Aye, 'tis the markets I miss the most, fair raven.~
@979  = ~Curiosity shops? We have those here on the Prime, you know.~
@980  = ~What kind of superstitions?~
@981  = ~Handmaidens? Why would some lady's handmaidens be interesting?~
@982  = ~You mentioned thugs and harlots - are these sort common in Sigil?~
@983  = ~The brothel of... what now?~
@984  = ~Let's talk about something else.~
@985  = ~Oh, aye, I have browsed a few here myself, but none can compare to the wild madness found in a city that touches all planes. 'Tis not uncommon for foolish youths to dare one another to buy an item at random without knowing its possible uses, just to see what will happen. The outcomes were... unpredictable, to say the least.~
@986  = ~Ah, memories...~
@987  = ~There are quite a many more than I could name, and some are not at all dissimilar to the paranoid beliefs I see here on the Prime. In the City of Doors, however, most fear stems from the threat of the ever-present Lady of Pain and her swift and merciless wrath. Almost all residents believe that simply to speak her name aloud is to tempt fate. I knew many otherwise perfectly reasonable folk who would fall apart or stare about in terror at the merest mention of the Lady!~
@988  = ~I don't understand. Who is the Lady of Pain?~
@989  = ~That seems pretty extreme.~
@990  = ~That's insane.~
@991  = ~Interesting.~
@992  = ~I can understand the poor rabble clinging to their bizzare beliefs, but even the educated believe that nonsense?~
@993  = ~Is she really as dangerous as they believe?~
@994  = ~They must have good reason to fear her so much.~
@995  = ~The Lady of Pain is the silent, ruthless and ever-vigilant ruler of my fair Sigil, though I often wonder if that is the title she would use for herself. 'Tis she who maintains the balance and preserves the neutrality of her Cage, opening and barring what portals she will, when she will. Despite her obvious power, the Lady refuses to be worshiped and will not long tolerate mockery, bringing about a swift end to any and all who dare test her patience. As far as this frail sparrow can tell, all the Lady of Pain desires is Sigil's continued stability.~
@996  = ~Aye, as are most blind beliefs. Though the Lady is clearly not one to be trifled with, 'tis obvious she does not sit about, wringing her hands, waiting to overhear her name in casual conversation so that she might Maze the poor berk.~
@997  = ~In truth, it might be reasonable to say that the wealthy and powerful fear the Lady even more, for 'tis they who stand out above the crowd and have much to lose. You must understand, the Lady herself is no myth. She is very real, and she wields terrible power, my dear raven.~
@998  = ~Oh, aye. Though I believe that many of the superstitions surrounding her are exaggerated or downright foolish, the Lady herself is no myth. She is very real, and she wields terrible power, my dear raven.~
@999  = ~Oh, not just *some* lady - *the* Lady. The handmaidens I refer to are the dabus, strange floating creatures with sickly skin and brilliant white hair. They are most curious beings, speaking only in rebuses that many find difficult to comprehend. They are the keepers of Sigil, tireless workers who labor to maintain buildings and streets.~
@1000 = ~Who is this Lady you speak of?~
@1001 = ~So these dabus are... women?~
@1002 = ~They *float*?~
@1003 = ~What are rebuses?~
@1004 = ~So, they're slaves.~
@1005 = ~I... No, I would not say that. Nor would I say they are male either. 'Tis something of a mystery, that, though the same question surrounds the Lady of Pain herself, whom many describe as not a lady at all. Mayhap the answer will be made clear someday, but this sparrow has no desire to go poking at that particular nest of vipers.~
@1006 = ~Indeed. They move to and fro suspended above the ground, much like the djinni. It is quite something to watch them at work, unfettered by the need to keep their feet on the ground.~
@1007 = ~A rebus is a sort of puzzle where pictures represent words or phrases or pieces of words. It sounds far simpler than it is, though this bard never had much trouble understanding the dabus. 'Tis most amusing to watch the Clueless attempt to sort it all out, though. Hah!~
@1008 = ~In truth, I do not know. Only the Lady could answer that for certain, and no one foolish enough to ask her would live to pass the truth on to anyone else. Some say that the dabus are training to replace the Lady when she dies, and others still claim the Lady has already died many times and been seamlessly replaced by one of her handmaidens. 'Tis all wild speculation, however, and considered a dangerous topic in the Cage.~
@1009 = ~Cities of the Prime are often rife with the less morally inclined elements of society, and Sigil is much the same only in far greater number. Walk down the wrong alley and you will find yourself surrounded. Turn the wrong corner and you will be assaulted, either by eager ladies of the night or by bloodthirsty thugs. In my home, the man who can make himself inconspicuous and unimportant in the eyes of those watching him is the man who lives a long life.~
@1010 = ~Mistress Grace's brothel, aye, run by the Sensates. I never had the pleasure of meeting the lovely succubus who first owned it, but the tales of her are most intriguing. The brothel itself is a most peculiar experience, my raven, focusing not on stimulation of the body but on stimulation of the *mind*. I daresay, you might enjoy it very much indeed.~
@1011 = ~I would *never* go to a brothel!~
@1012 = ~That's disgusting.~
@1013 = ~Stimulation of the mind? What does that mean?~
@1014 = ~What is a 'Sensate?'~
@1015 = ~Sounds fascinating.~
@1016 = ~I'm always open to new brothel experiences.~
@1017 = ~Tsk, a pity.~
@1018 = ~Patrons often engage in lengthy discussions or games that are very challenging. 'Tis difficult to describe, I fear, and is best understood through experience.~
@1019 = ~The Society of Sensation is one of the many factions of Sigil. They hold that life is a long and winding series of experiences - sensations, as it were - and only through these feelings can true enlightenment be reached. They are a interesting lot, if this sparrow may say so.~
@1020 = ~Should you find yourself in Sigil someday, I heartily recommend you visit the fair establishment yourself, my dear <CHARNAME>.~
@1021 = ~Shall I go on, or have you thought of something in particular you wish to know?~
@1022 = ~You mentioned superstitions. What kinds?~
@1023 = ~Why would some lady's handmaidens be interesting?~
@1024 = ~You said something about a brothel...~
@1025 = ~'Tis a city, my raven, but one unlike any you've ever before beheld. It resides atop the infinite Spiral at the heart of the Concordant Opposition. The City of Doors it is called, and for good reason, for Sigil contains portals to every Plane in existence. It is a nexus, a meeting point, a cross roads, and a prison.~
@1026 = ~Aye, it is a cage, *the* Cage, some would say, with innumerable entrances and exits, and all of them locked. Without a key, there is no escape. But with the right key, or the right connections... my raven, the possibilities are endless.~
@1027 = ~And you lived in this cage?~
@1028 = ~Just how many portals are we talking about?~
@1029 = ~When you say 'key' I somehow doubt you mean the small metal sort for chests and frontdoors.~
@1030 = ~That sounds amazing.~
@1031 = ~What you describe is hard to believe.~
@1032 = ~I have spent most of my life within Sigil's embrace. It is where I was born, and is the only place which compels me to return. One might say it is the only cage I submit myself to willingly.~
@1033 = ~Numbers beyond measure, my friend, and in shapes and sizes that vary widely. Doorways, windows, picture frames - passing through any of these and so many more could whisk you away to the planes in the blink of an eye!~
@1034 = ~In Sigil, a key can be anything - an object, a person, a word or phrase, even an emotion. If a person should wish to travel somewhere specific, it is reasonable to declare it impossible without knowledge of the portal's location and its key. Of course, it can be a simple thing to wander the wards and happen upon an open portal to *somewhere*, but... well, it is never wise to jump out the window, my raven.~
@1035 = ~Perhaps someday you will see it with your own eyes. It is truly magnificent.~
@1036 = ~Was there something in particular you wished to ask?~
@1037 = ~Nothing specific, really. Perhaps you could just tell me something of your experiences there?~
@1038 = ~Thank you. That's all I wanted to know.~
@1039 = ~Of course. I hope I've sufficiently satisfied your curiosity.~
@1040 = ~At first glance, it is not all that unlike the cities of Amn, full of buildings, vendors, crowded streets, a diverse populace wandering hither and yon. But when one takes a moment to look more closely...~
@1041 = ~You see, Sigil itself is shaped like a torus, a hollow tube curved in on itself to form a perfect circle, with the city spanning the entirety of the inner wall. There is no sky overhead as you are accustomed to seeing, no sun or moon or stars. When a person looks up, there is another part of the city looking down.~
@1042 = ~It likely sounds very strange to you.~
@1043 = ~Yes, very strange.~
@1044 = ~Actually, it sounds fascinating.~
@1045 = ~It sounds dangerous.~
@1046 = ~Eh, it doesn't sound all that impressive.~
@1047 = ~Many of the Clueless who passed through the city said the same, but I must admit that your Prime seems just as odd to this sparrow at times.~
@1048 = ~It is indeed, even to one such as myself who has known it all of his days. It holds many secrets, more than this sparrow could ever hope to discover, and perhaps that above all else is why I return to my home again and again.~
@1049 = ~Oh, it certainly is, but so is Athkatla, is it not? In Sigil, just as in any city of the Prime, the key is to avoid ignorance. Behaving like a common berk will get a person killed, as will being unprepared or lazy, or drawing too much attention to oneself.~
@1050 = ~But these things are common sense for most reasonable creatures, aye? Or they very well should be.~
@1051 = ~This humble bard's words cannot do it justice. Someday, if you are able, I suggest you travel there to see it for yourself.~
@1052 = ~Many, many creatures, from everywhere you can imagine and beyond. Only deities are forbidden to enter the city, and those who tempt my Lady Pain's wrath do not survive to repeat their mistake.~
@1053 = ~Tanar'ri, baatezu and all their various forms of progeny are common enough, as is your race and other races of the Prime. From the mysterious native dabus, to the hulking thokola, to the honorable four-footed bariaur, Sigil is a city of wild and vast diversity that touches every ward from the Hive to the Markets and beyond. There, this sparrow would not be surprised to see an aasimar sharing drinks with a githyanki and an abishai, or a drow entertaining a celestial at a brothel.~
@1054 = ~All these races exist together peacefully?~
@1055 = ~It sounds terribly complicated.~
@1056 = ~How chaotic it must be.~
@1057 = ~Weird. I don't think I'd like it much.~
@1058 = ~Not in the least. As long as the stability of Sigil is not threatened, its inhabitants are free to do as they please - *if* they can survive the consequences, of course. That isn't to say the city is a constant battlefield, but violence and bloodshed are commonplace.~
@1059 = ~I suppose it is, especially to one who has not grown up exposed to such things. To this bard, it is simply 'home.'~
@1060 = ~Hah! So you can easily guess why this sparrow finds it so very appealing, aye?~
@1061 = ~It can be overwhelming, even to one such as myself. Still, I adore the madness and chaos that can only be found in Sigil.~
@1062 = ~Fifteen separate factions rule o'er the day-to-day functions of the city, each with their own agendas and personal dogmas, scrabbling and scrapping for as much power as they can hold without drawing the Lady's ire. I, as one of the Doomguard, count myself among their number. Yet none of them would exist if it were not the will of the one and only true ruler of Sigil.~
@1063 = ~The Lady of Pain, silent and ruthless, ever watches over her domain. 'Tis she who maintains the balance and preserves the neutrality of her Cage, opening and barring what portals she will, when she will. No one and nothing passes through the City of Doors without her knowledge. Her rule is law, and to defy her laws is to invite a brutal death. Or worse.~
@1064 = ~'Or worse?'~
@1065 = ~Is she some kind of god?~
@1066 = ~Have you seen her?~
@1067 = ~Bah, she sounds like another one of your tall tales.~
@1068 = ~It is said that the lucky ones are flayed alive, but that those who have truly angered the Lady are taken to one of her private Mazes. There they are doomed to wander without hope of escape, slowly slipping into madness. A terrifying prospect, if you want this bard's opinion.~
@1069 = ~Perhaps. Very little is known of her, and any who attempt to learn more are killed or vanish without a trace. She is one of the few true mysteries in the multiverse, and perhaps the only one I have no desire to investigate.~
@1070 = ~I...~
@1071 = ~Once, my raven. From a distance.~
@1072 = ~Let us just say that I have no desire to repeat the experience, and we shall let the subject rest.~
@1073 = ~Then do not believe me, my hound, but I would not visit the Cage while such doubts dwell in your mind.~
@1074 = ~Why, my dear raven, a planewalker is precisely as the name implies: one who walks the planes.~
@1075 = ~Surely there's more to it than that.~
@1076 = ~Is there some kind of requirement for being a walker of the planes?~
@1077 = ~Huh. Ask a stupid question...~
@1078 = ~Conversing with you always leaves me with a headache.~
@1079 = ~It is surprisingly uncomplicated, my raven.~
@1080 = ~If you mean rules or guidelines, most certainly not. 'Twould hardly be a life that appeals to this bard if it were so.~
@1081 = ~Tsk, come now! There are no stupid questions.~
@1082 = ~Well, that's not true. But this question of yours was not one.~
@1083 = ~Oh delightful hound, you have no idea how often the feeling is mutual.~
@1084 = ~There are some common traits in many of those who choose to walk the planes. Nearly all are practitioners of magic, perhaps more out of expedience than necessity. Most planewalkers choose to travel alone, but for this sparrow it is preferable to have some companionship. What is an actor without an audience, after all?~
@1085 = ~Of course, while we are rightly called plane*walkers*, walking itself is not truly a requirement. Some of us run, or crawl, or perhaps float, and I even once met a man who danced his way across the planes. Strange fellow. Just watching him prance along made this sparrow weary.~
@1086 = ~But truly there are very little in the way of absolutes when it comes to planar travel.~
@1087 = ~So anyone can do it?~
@1088 = ~But, *why*? Why spend your whole life wandering in strange places?~
@1089 = ~It sounds amazing, Haer'Dalis.~
@1090 = ~You prefer to have company with you, hmm?~
@1091 = ~Yeah, I didn't need to know all that, so are you finished now?~
@1092 = ~Well, I suppose anyone *could* do it, but the better question might be whether someone *should*. 'Tis not a life for everyone, that much is certain.~
@1093 = ~To see sights that few eyes have e'er beheld. To be the first to set my boots into exotic lands. To find an audience who has never before seen this sparrow, and watch the awe on their faces as they see me perform for the first time. To meet new and unexpected companions.~
@1094 = ~To meet people like you, my raven.~
@1095 = ~I know it is not a life that all can enjoy, but there is no other life for this Doomguard.~
@1096 = ~Does it? Mayhap you wish to experience it for yourself, once all this madness of the moment has been put behind you?~
@1097 = ~Me? You mean anyone can be a planewalker?~
@1098 = ~Honestly, I don't understand why someone would want to spend their whole life wandering in strange places.~
@1099 = ~I would love to!~
@1100 = ~Maybe.~
@1101 = ~Oh, I doubt it.~
@1102 = ~If I did, it wouldn't be with you.~
@1103 = ~I do indeed, my dear <CHARNAME>. Why? Mayhap you wish to join this bard and experience it for yourself, once all this madness of the moment has been put behind you?~
@1104 = ~No, I was just clarifying. You are truly weak if you need constant companionship.~
@1105 = ~<CHARNAME>, at these moments you seem less a raven and more a vulture.~
@1106 = ~Ah, but surely I've said enough to sate your curiosity for the moment. All this talk has me eager to stretch my legs. Let us put our boots to the road!~
@1107 = ~It would be my infinite pleasure to introduce you to the life of a planewalker. Provided we survive our current adventure, of course.~
@1108 = ~Should you wish it, I would be delighted to introduce you to the life of a planewalker. Provided we survive our current adventure, of course.~
@1109 = ~A pity. You would doubtless cause as much chaos and destruction across all planes as you do here in your own Prime, and I would be most pleased to see it.~
@1110 = ~How fortunate for me.~
@1111 = ~Surely you are not blind to the irony of you speaking those words to me, my darling hound.~
@1112 = ~We are the guardians of decay, the saboteurs of meaning, the agents of destiny. And that destiny is that all things falter, all things fail. The multiverse is a snake that has caught its tail in its mouth... and begun to swallow.~
@1113 = ~And what happens when this 'snake' finishes swallowing?~
@1114 = ~So... what? You just wander around causing chaos wherever you go?~
@1115 = ~Are the Doomguard an order? An army? A culture?~
@1116 = ~I see. Thank you for the explanation.~
@1117 = ~What a depressing view of the realms.~
@1118 = ~Then, my raven, the world will be made perfect through destruction.~
@1119 = ~Anything else you wish to know?~
@1120 = ~Are Doomguards an order? An army? A culture?~
@1121 = ~No, that's clear enough. Thank you for the explanation.~
@1122 = ~Hah! Do I imagine the way you leer at this sparrow when you ask that?~
@1123 = ~Some of us spread chaos, certainly. Others revel in more direct destruction. Ours is not a philosophy that can only be approached from one direction.~
@1124 = ~Perhaps a little of everything. We are one of the fifteen factions of the City of Doors, our headquarters being Sigil's Armory. Those who revel in destruction must have the proper tools, aye? There we forge weapons to spread our influence.~
@1125 = ~You are most welcome.~
@1126 = ~Do you think so? Odd. I find it quite the opposite.~
@1127 = ~What a peculiar question, my raven. 'Tis difficult to answer, as I've never been anything else. Was there something in particular you wished to know?~
@1128 = ~You don't mind, do you? I don't want to seem rude.~
@1129 = ~What is a tiefling, exactly?~
@1130 = ~No, not really. I just wondered if there was anything odd or interesting about your heritage.~
@1131 = ~Do you have any strange urges?~
@1132 = ~You don't really look like a tiefling.~
@1133 = ~I suppose you and I have something in common, both of us bearing tainted blood and all.~
@1134 = ~Forget I asked.~
@1135 = ~Oh, this sparrow does not protest your interest in the least. You are not the first to find me curious, my raven, and I much prefer the attention of your questions to wary sidelong glances.~
@1136 = ~I didn't really want to know anything in particular. I just wondered if there was anything odd or interesting about your heritage.~
@1137 = ~Very well. Do you have any strange urges?~
@1138 = ~As you wish, my raven.~
@1139 = ~A tiefling, my dear lady, is the offspring of a Prime, often a human or an elf, and any denizen of the lower planes. This sparrow is the product of a union between a demoness and an elven sire.~
@1140 = ~Oh, there is a fine mix of both, I'm sure. I am told I have an aura that makes Primes feel uneasy, and they sometimes complain of the scent of sulfur on my skin, though I think they exaggerate.~
@1141 = ~No, I've noticed both myself.~
@1142 = ~I think so, too. I've never felt uneasy around you.~
@1143 = ~Oh, trust me, the smell is definitely there.~
@1144 = ~I've never noticed anything like that.~
@1145 = ~Truly? And you never complained? I suppose I should be grateful.~
@1146 = ~'Tis a pleasure to hear you say so, my sweet raven.~
@1147 = ~I shall simply pretend you are not implying that I stink and move this conversation forward.~
@1148 = ~Was there something else you wished to ask?~
@1149 = ~No, that's all I wished to know.~
@1150 = ~Hmm... I occasionally feel the uncontrollable longing for cinnamon. Alas, 'tis a vice I admit freely! Mmm, the craving has hit me...~
@1151 = ~Oh, do not look at me so. I understood your question well enough. My blood occasionally leads me to flirt with situations I might not otherwise dare to try, but in the average day, I sense little influence from it. 'Twas quite different when this sparrow served in the Blood War for a short while, of course.~
@1152 = ~What is the Blood War?~
@1153 = ~You served in the Blood War?~
@1154 = ~Different how?~
@1155 = ~Strange. I expected you'd feel more influenced by your blood.~
@1156 = ~I expected as much. You don't seem like you're struggling for control or anything like that.~
@1157 = ~The eternal conflict between tanar'ri and baatezu, my raven. I find it surprising you've not heard of it.~
@1158 = ~Aye, that I did, for only a year and yet that was plenty long for this poor sparrow.~
@1159 = ~Perhaps we can discuss it another time.~
@1160 = ~Perhaps you are projecting your own struggles upon this sparrow.~
@1161 = ~Oh, believe you me, I struggle for control on occasion, but 'tis typically not my blood that I rage against. There are other passions that overwhelm me at times.~
@1162 = ~Aye? And how many tieflings have you seen, my raven, to make such a judgement?~
@1163 = ~Well, none actually.~
@1164 = ~A few here and there.~
@1165 = ~I thought most have tails and horns and such, and yet you have none of that.~
@1166 = ~Then how would you know what to look for, I wonder.~
@1167 = ~'Tis true that many of mixed blood bear markings of their heritage, but it is hardly a rule. The color of my hair does suggest something unusual in my blood, but that perhaps can be attributed to my elven sire.~
@1168 = ~Perhaps we might. Considering the inclinations of your late father, I imagine our blood could lead us both down rather different paths than the ones before us now, aye? But to live like a beast and be used by any inclination other than my own thoughts and desires? The idea brings me unease and curiosity in equal measure.~
@1169 = ~I'd never let my blood rule me.~
@1170 = ~Being a bit beastly every now and again has its appeal.~
@1171 = ~I cannot imagine a more bloody path than the one I'm on right now.~
@1172 = ~The taint does not use me - *I* use the taint, and it bends to my will and makes me stronger.~
@1173 = ~Never? Oh, never sounds terribly boring, if you ask this sparrow.~
@1174 = ~Oh, on that we must agree.~
@1175 = ~I can, my raven. I can.~
@1176 = ~Do you? I suppose only time will tell. This sparrow wonders if he will live long enough to see you discover the truth.~
@1177 = ~'Twas as natural as breathing, my raven. Verse and song and acting - aye, foremost acting - have ever been in this sparrow's heart as far back as my memory goes.~
@1178 = ~I feel much the same.~
@1179 = ~It was never quite so effortless for me as you make it sound for you.~
@1180 = ~It sounds wonderful. I'm a little jealous, to be honest.~
@1181 = ~Hmph, poetic rubbish. What nonsense~
@1182 = ~You were never tempted to pursue any other profession?~
@1183 = ~I doubt it was as effortless as you make it sound.~
@1184 = ~That makes sense, I suppose.~
@1185 = ~Aye, we are much akin in these matters, are we not? I find it most delightful to travel in the company of one who understands my inner workings so well.~
@1186 = ~Oh, I do not mean to imply that it was without trials. There were moments of terrible doubt, moments when I had convinced myself that I would be better off scrubbing chamberpots in some filthy inn. But those thoughts never lasted overlong, and each time I would wake in a gutter, I would drag myself out again.~
@1187 = ~Nonsense. You are an artist at what you do, my dear <CHARNAME>. Be proud!~
@1188 = ~Ah, just what this sparrow needs. A critic.~
@1189 = ~I most certainly was indeed. I dreamed of being a mercenary, of relying solely on my blades and my wits to see me through, but... Well, let us just say that one cannot hide from who they are.~
@1190 = ~I suppose it is most truthful to say that the Art chose me, rather than the other way 'round. For a time, I put much effort into ignoring its call, but it soon became clear that I was as likely to escape the need to breathe as avoid my calling.~
@1191 = ~Such a question is considered socially improper, is it not?~
@1192 = ~Only if a man asks a woman.~
@1193 = ~I suppose so. I apologize.~
@1194 = ~It may be rude, but I'd still like to know.~
@1195 = ~Not at all.~
@1196 = ~Stop dodging the question.~
@1197 = ~Hmph. I say, that does seem rather unfair, my raven.~
@1198 = ~My raven, are you always so quick to retreat? 'Tis not a desirable trait in a leader, I must say.~
@1199 = ~I will tell you the number of my years, but only after you guess at the answer.~
@1200 = ~I hate guessing games.~
@1201 = ~Oh, I love guessing games!~
@1202 = ~I assume you're older than you appear, considering your planar blood.~
@1203 = ~I wouldn't even know where to begin to guess, though.~
@1204 = ~You can't be that much older than I am.~
@1205 = ~Oh, just tell me!~
@1206 = ~Never mind. Forget I asked.~
@1207 = ~Then, if not love, you shall at least learn to tolerate them if you wish me to entertain your query.~
@1208 = ~Truly? Then glad I am you shall find delight in this, my raven.~
@1209 = ~Why, simply pick a number, of course.~
@1210 = ~I assure you, I am.~
@1211 = ~My but you are an impatient one. *sigh* As you wish, my hound.~
@1212 = ~I suppose that would depend upon how old I appear in your estimation.~
@1213 = ~You look rather young to me. No more than thirty, I would guess.~
@1214 = ~You speak with wisdom born of experience, so I'd guess you are at least in your forties.~
@1215 = ~Honestly, I don't know.~
@1216 = ~Your humble sparrow admits that he is now eighty and six years of age. I believe I had a birthday pass me by just recently, in fact.~
@1217 = ~Eighty-six?!~
@1218 = ~You certainly look good for your age.~
@1219 = ~That explains the way you talk.~
@1220 = ~No wonder you look so tired and worn at times.~
@1221 = ~Your birthday? You should have told me! I'd have gotten you a present.~
@1222 = ~How long do you think you might expect to live, were you to survive to be an old man?~
@1223 = ~Pfft, what nonsense. You cannot possibly be that old.~
@1224 = ~I see. Thank you for telling me.~
@1225 = ~You are most welcome, of course.~
@1226 = ~Aye, I have seen and done much in my years. That these experiences reveal themselves through my tone comes as little surprise to me, and you are not the first to remark on it.~
@1227 = ~I beg you, my raven, say not such things to your poor frail sparrow! Entropy shall surely take me over, but I face such decay with a glad heart and no regrets. Any weariness you see in me is surely the result of your driving leadership, aye?~
@1228 = ~My dear sweet raven, you are beautiful beyond measure. Such a delightful sentiment is enough to warm this sparrow through and through.~
@1229 = ~My blood is influenced by both the longevity of the tanar'ri and the agelessness of the elves. I cannot be certain how many years this body would provide, granted I am not eaten by some fearful creature you happen across in our travels, but I would not be surprised to see two hundred years or more with parents such as mine.~
@1230 = ~But surely your question has been adequately replied, aye? Let us return to our tasks and test the length of my life, if only for a short while longer.~
@1231 = ~My but you are a forward one, aren't you? 'Tis no critique, mind you, but such a direct approach is indeed rare, especially here on the Prime.~
@1232 = ~I am flattered by your request, dear raven, but I fear I must decline. I shall take your example and be perfectly blunt. Whilst your request is a simple one, and a pleasing one, *you* <CHARNAME>, are not quite so simple. In this particular case, this sparrow would very much like to know what exactly he is getting into before diving in, if you'll pardon the tawdry imagery.~
@1233 = ~That is not to say my mind may not change, of course. It has a habit of doing precisely that.~
@1234 = ~Ah. I suppose I did promise to answer any question I first asked you, aye?~
@1235 = ~That you did.~
@1236 = ~If it makes you uncomfortable, you don't have to tell me.~
@1237 = ~I just want to know more about you.~
@1238 = ~Don't play coy, bard.~
@1239 = ~I hardly expect you to tell the truth, so you might as well begin your fantastical tale.~
@1240 = ~'Tis not my discomfort for which I fear, but yours.~
@1241 = ~I will not lie. Your curiosity is most flattering.~
@1242 = ~Oh? Will the truth disappoint you then, I wonder?~
@1243 = ~This story of mine, it is not a short one, but if you wish to hear it, I shall grant you the insight you seek.~
@1244 = ~It would mean a lot to me.~
@1245 = ~Get on with it then.~
@1246 = ~Can you give me an abridged version, perhaps?~
@1247 = ~On second thought, let's just leave the past in the past.~
@1248 = ~As you would have it, my raven.~
@1249 = ~Hmm... my father was an elf with a fetish for planar blood who experimented on various bloodlines of tanar'ri and baatezu. My mother was a rather temperamental cambion. I was the product of one of my father's experiments, though I have been blissfully free of either of their interference for many years now. Does that suffice?~
@1250 = ~Whoa, perhaps the long version would be better after all.~
@1251 = ~It does. Thank you for sharing that with me.~
@1252 = ~When was the last time you saw either of them?~
@1253 = ~What rubbish. I knew you'd spin a yarn instead of telling me the truth.~
@1254 = ~You are most welcome, my sweet friend.~
@1255 = ~I last saw my father as he fled through a dimensional rift to I know not where, my sister in tow. My mother... she I last saw during my time in the Blood War, conscripted at her recommendation.~
@1256 = ~I beg your pardon, my friend, but I've lost my appetite for this topic. If we could move on, I would be most grateful.~
@1257 = ~Ah, but of course it is a lie. Clearly it would make much more believable a tale if I said my fairfolk father was madly in love with my demonic mother and we lived in blissful happiness all of our days until some great tragedy tore me from their embrace.~
@1258 = ~Surely, my raven, you do not believe you are the only creature in the realms with an unbelievable childhood.~
@1259 = ~As you wish. My sire was an elf, a moon elf if that matters to you, and a rather powerful mage. Or a *very* powerful mage, by his own estimation. He moved from his fair home on the Prime when he was in his second century of life to build a tower in Sigil where he could conduct his research with less criticism and scrutiny.~
@1260 = ~Go on.~
@1261 = ~What kind of research?~
@1262 = ~Scrutiny? Was he meddling in things his fellow elves disapproved of?~
@1263 = ~I am unsure what his initial studies focused upon, but his interest eventually settled most obsessively upon the properties and abilities associated with the blood of the denizens of the lower planes.~
@1264 = ~Oh, most assuredly.~
@1265 = ~He began to experiment on various races of tanar'ri and baatezu, though he was careful in the beginning to avoid drawing attention to himself. He would bribe his subjects, or simply charm a creature whom no one would miss. There are many such beings in the City of Doors.~
@1266 = ~Eventually he grew bolder, abducting stronger, more powerful creatures to test his theories upon, and he took great pride in his collection of both living and dead specimens. My mother was one such prize.~
@1267 = ~You mean... your father caged and tortured these people?!~
@1268 = ~I don't understand. Was he trying to create a harem, or some sort of army of progeny to carry on his name or something?~
@1269 = ~Clearly you inherited your boldness and reckless tendencies from your father.~
@1270 = ~Your poor mother...~
@1271 = ~That and more, I'm sure. He was ambitious, blindly so, and only his experiments and theories mattered to him.~
@1272 = ~Even to this day, I do not fully understand his goals. 'Twas not about him, or so he always insisted, but about something greater, something for the future of elven kind.~
@1273 = ~My raven, I take that comparison as a compliment.~
@1274 = ~Hah! Perhaps I should tell you a bit about her before you waste your sympathies.~
@1275 = ~The battle to cage my mother was a long one indeed. Father often referred to her as 'the one who nearly got away.' She was the first of his pets that he allowed to conceive a child by him, though she tried many times to tear her unborn babe from her womb if that tells you anything of her feelings on the matter.~
@1276 = ~For all the trouble my father went to in his efforts to make certain I was born unharmed, it appears he was a victim of his own high expectations. I was not what he sought to create, and that became only the more obvious as the years passed.~
@1277 = ~Go on. ~
@1278 = ~That's horrible, Haer'Dalis.~
@1279 = ~What was so disappointing about you?~
@1280 = ~I still don't understand. What was he trying to create?~
@1281 = ~Do not look upon me with pity. 'Twas such a beginning that showed me the truth of the multiverse.~
@1282 = ~I was too much artist, and not enough fanatic. My mind did not dance to the tunes he sang, and for that he despaired.~
@1283 = ~Perfection, my raven. He sought perfection.~
@1284 = ~When my failures became too obvious to ignore, he created a new child, this time with a baatezu. Unlike my mother, this planar creature was most pleased to aid my father's research willingly. In my half-sister, he believed he'd found the answer to his question.~
@1285 = ~Unfortunately, he was unable to enjoy his supposed success for long. I was but a young man, and my sister little more than a child when my mother escaped her bonds.~
@1286 = ~And she wanted revenge?~
@1287 = ~Escaped, or was set free?~
@1288 = ~You still lived with him, despite his rejection?~
@1289 = ~Of course. Would you not desire the same had you been caged and tormented, forced to take part in unspeakable horrors against your will?~
@1290 = ~Ah... it matters little, my hound. Freedom was her goal, and freedom she received.~
@1291 = ~Perhaps you misunderstand. 'Twas not a free life that I lived. My father's home was a prison to all within its walls... himself included.~
@1292 = ~Mother's wrath razed the tower to the ground, but Father and his perfect child fled through a planar rift just as the fighting broke out. When the dust settled, all who had survived the chaos found themselves suddenly free of my father's influence. This sparrow included.~
@1293 = ~That's an astounding tale.~
@1294 = ~No offense, but that sounds really farfetched.~
@1295 = ~And that was the last you saw of your parents?~
@1296 = ~Did you ever see your sister again?~
@1297 = ~My father, yes. My mother... she I last saw the day I was conscripted into the Blood Wars, at her recommendation.~
@1298 = ~Ah, and I did not even think to add my usual embellishments. A pity, as you'd surely be gawking in speechless wonder if I had.~
@1299 = ~Many have said the same of your own exploits.~
@1300 = ~Aye, that I did. That, however, is a tale for another time.~
@1301 = ~Ah, lovely Saalyn, fierce half-devil, unmatched in her prowess with a blade. What do you wish to know of her?~
@1302 = ~Were you close?~
@1303 = ~What is she like?~
@1304 = ~Where is she?~
@1305 = ~Ah, forget I mentioned her.~
@1306 = ~Very well.~
@1307 = ~As close as any two baatezu and tanar'ri ever can be, I suppose. When we were young and living under our father's thumb, I was not permitted to interact with her or even see her for more than a few moments at a time. Father feared I would taint her perfection just by breathing the same air.~
@1308 = ~You sound bitter.~
@1309 = ~That must have felt horrible.~
@1310 = ~I'm sure it wasn't all that bad.~
@1311 = ~What about after you escaped your father?~
@1312 = ~Do I? Ah, my raven, I wish I could say you are wrong, but I fear there are some memories that will chafe until the end of my days regardless of how much time passes.~
@1313 = ~That it did. But... What is that saying I've heard? What does not kill us makes us stronger? Aye, I am grateful for the strength I've earned.~
@1314 = ~If that is what you wish to believe, then I am not inclined to correct you.~
@1315 = ~After the tower that was my home crumbled to dust and I stumbled alone into the streets of Sigil, I was certain I would never see my father, mother or Saalyn again. As the years passed and I heard not a whispered rumor of any of them, I only became more certain, and I was content to put the past behind me. After all, I had no reason to carry fondness for any of them.~
@1316 = ~Then one night, as I sang bawdy songs on a tiny, crumbling stage in a crowded brothel full of drunkards, there she was. Saalyn had found me.~
@1317 = ~It was just her?~
@1318 = ~Wait, go back to the part where you worked in a brothel.~
@1319 = ~She was looking for you?~
@1320 = ~The way you say that almost makes it sound like she wanted to kill you.~
@1321 = ~Aye.~
@1322 = ~Hah! My raven, you are very predictable. Believe it or not, this sparrow was not always the proud and mighty Doomguard you see now before you. As you well know, sometimes we must humble ourselves to survive.~
@1323 = ~That is precisely what I thought when our eyes met across the room.~
@1324 = ~The last time I saw Saalyn before that moment, our father still controlled her. For all I knew, she had been at his side all those years, training to be his perfect pet assassin. And now she was coming for me, to trim up the loose ends of my father's ragged legacy.~
@1325 = ~But that wasn't what she wanted at all.~
@1326 = ~She told me she had been on her own for years, that Father was dead - by her hand no less - and that she had been searching for me. She... she wanted me to show her how to live a normal life, because that was the one thing Father had denied her. I was not certain I could believe her, but time would prove her honesty, and I am glad she and I did not have to kill each other.~
@1327 = ~Was there something else you wished to know?~
@1328 = ~No, that's all. Thank you for telling me this.~
@1329 = ~Oh, where to begin? Saalyn is a warrior, hard, uncompromising, incapable of seeing life in shades of gray. The childhood she endured left her with very little in the way of compassion or humor. Surly at the best of times, cruel and murderous at her worst, she gained much temperance after a few years of association with yours truly.~
@1330 = ~She's very different from you.~
@1331 = ~She sounds like a horrible person.~
@1332 = ~So, she's strong.~
@1333 = ~What does she look like?~
@1334 = ~As different as night and day, as you Primes are fond of saying. Our mutual disdain for our deceased father was not all we shared, though, and I have many fond memories of my sister.~
@1335 = ~I suppose some might see her that way. She was certainly less than amiable when first we found each other again, but hers was a battered and wounded soul. I cannot blame her for what she became in that tower.~
@1336 = ~Aye, stronger than this sparrow even. I do not jest when I say she is my superior in open combat.~
@1337 = ~If I describe her ebony hair and ivory skin, you might easily picture a creature of beauty, but in reality Saalyn is a being built to destroy through violence and it shows in every aspect of her features. Like myself, she bears very few outward indicators of her planar parentage. One might think she is simply an unusually large elf at first glance.~
@1338 = ~Of that I cannot be entirely certain. I last saw her the day I fled to the Prime with Miss Raelis. Saalyn helped us escape a group of hunters very like the ones from which you rescued this humble sparrow.~
@1339 = ~Why didn't Saalyn come with you?~
@1340 = ~That was brave of her.~
@1341 = ~And you just left her behind like a coward?~
@1342 = ~Aye, it was. And I did not deserve such loyalty from her.~
@1343 = ~When my sister snarls an order, only a fool would refuse to follow it. Because she would simply knock him over the head and throw him through the portal anyway. (sigh)~
@1344 = ~You must understand, my raven, when I left Sigil there had not been peace between myself and my sister for many, many years.~
@1345 = ~She turned on you?~
@1346 = ~What happened?~
@1347 = ~I thought you had fond memories of her.~
@1348 = ~What did you do to drive her away?~
@1349 = ~Quite the opposite, I fear.~
@1350 = ~Oh, I do. I will continue to remember those times with fondness until the day I cease to breathe.~
@1351 = ~'Twas after my time in the Blood War that everything changed. Saalyn and I had been traveling together with a group of wayward minstrels for more than a decade when chance would have it that we crossed paths with the baalor lord my mother served. And in the blink of an eye, everything I knew was turned upside down.~
@1352 = ~It was more than a year before I escaped my captivity and fled back to Sigil. Saalyn found me shortly thereafter, but...~
@1353 = ~I don't understand. Shouldn't you have been happy?~
@1354 = ~Ah, I get it. Devils, demons, eternal battle and all that.~
@1355 = ~You really expect me to believe that you were completely changed after just a year?~
@1356 = ~I was happy. But it was not enough.~
@1357 = ~I do not know if I can adequately explain it to one who is not of the planes. It is not as simple as saying 'baatezu and tanar'ri must always kill each other.' Many of both dwell in Sigil, and they are not constantly at war. Despite what I've heard other tieflings claim, *I* do not feel the urge to tear the throat from every baatezu spawn whose path I might cross.~
@1358 = ~Yet, when Saalyn would sit near me... I could sense her presence like a festering burn beneath my skin. I could hear my mother's whispers, my master's commands, urging me to kill her before she betrayed me. I was utterly convinced that Saalyn meant me harm.~
@1359 = ~Did she?~
@1360 = ~It sounds like you were under some sort of enchantment.~
@1361 = ~You were too weak to resist your mother's manipulations.~
@1362 = ~Did you try to kill her?~
@1363 = ~If she had wished me dead, my sister could have killed me on numerous occasions.~
@1364 = ~Perhaps. It makes little difference now.~
@1365 = ~Indeed I was, and I have suffered for it.~
@1366 = ~No.~
@1367 = ~I drove Saalyn away, distanced myself from her in every possible way. It was around that time that I began to roam the planes in earnest. I wrapped myself in the Doomguard philosophy and discovered the truth that had evaded me for so long. I lost myself in my pursuits, in my Art and my travels, and I changed much over the next few decades.~
@1368 = ~I would see Saalyn when my wanderings brought me back to Sigil. The uneasiness I suffered in her presence after the Blood War faded to nothing as time passed, but the damage had already been done. The easy friendship we once nurtured never returned.~
@1369 = ~Still, I was and ever will be grateful for my sister. After all, my dear raven, 'twas Saalyn who first introduced me to Miss Raelis, and if I had not taken up with my former mistress, you and I would never have met.~
@1370 = ~My raven, I am loath to withhold any tale from you, but surely you will forgive me if I decline to answer.~
@1371 = ~That bad, huh?~
@1372 = ~Oh, come on! Please?~
@1373 = ~I never thought a Doomguard would have trouble discussing his past.~
@1374 = ~Why don't you want to talk about it?~
@1375 = ~You're even weaker than I thought if you cannot stomach a simple discussion.~
@1376 = ~Worse, my friend. Far, far worse than anything you can imagine, and a thousand times less meaningful. Perhaps that is what bothers me most about the Blood War. It is fully, utterly and in all possible ways the most *pointless* war ever fought.~
@1377 = ~I beg you, <CHARNAME>, do not look at me so. I do not enjoy denying you anything, but I have no desire whatsoever to relive this bit of my past.~
@1378 = ~This sparrow is not perfect. As much as I wish at times that I could detach myself from the emotional entanglements of past events, alas that I am a mere mortal and must suffer through my own weaknesses.~
@1379 = ~<CHARNAME>, 'twas nothing but blood and death and screams and madness. And while normally I am one to revel in such things, the violence of the Blood War is not one I can embrace.~
@1380 = ~'Tis not the discussion that turns my stomach. 'Tis the remembering.~
@1381 = ~Thank you.~
@1382 = ~Now, let us return to the road.~
@1383 = ~Oh, probably somewhere around the last place I left her. The Abyss, if I recall correctly. The Sixth Pyre, perhaps? No, it had to have been Hollow's Heart. Or was that... hmm...~
@1384 = ~Well, regardless of where she is, she is surely busying herself by proving how terribly useful she is to the nearest tanar'ri with the most power.~
@1385 = ~So, she's still alive?~
@1386 = ~Being your father's prisoner must have been a real inconvenience for her then.~
@1387 = ~Why did she drag you into the Blood War?~
@1388 = ~I see. Well, let's get moving.~
@1389 = ~Of course, my raven.~
@1390 = ~She is a cambion, my raven, an immortal demon. Though I suppose your sire was immortal once and look how that turned out for him. Still, the likelihood that someone has discovered a permanent way to rid the planes of my mother is rather slim.~
@1391 = ~Let me get this straight. You believe that all things fade and die, that decay and entropy come for everything, yet your own mother is *immortal*?~
@1392 = ~I'm surprised you didn't try to kill her after all she put you through.~
@1393 = ~Aye, well. I have never claimed life was without irony.~
@1394 = ~Honestly, this sparrow was only interested in escape. By the time I had the freedom to entertain thoughts of revenge, I was too far away to do anything with them.~
@1395 = ~Was there something more you wish to ask, or should we return to the road?~
@1396 = ~No, I don't have anymore questions. Let's go.~
@1397 = ~Hah! Aye, it was most inconvenient indeed, though I cannot truly blame her for resenting her cage.~
@1398 = ~How did she really escape?~
@1399 = ~No, I wouldn't want to be locked up by some mad mage either...~
@1400 = ~Sounds like she belonged in a cage.~
@1401 = ~I freed her.~
@1402 = ~Make no mistake, 'twas not charity that guided my hand, but selfish desire to see an end to my father and all he held dear. And... perhaps I could not bear to see her caged any longer. No good deed goes unpunished, aye?~
@1403 = ~My raven, you simply must work on your subtlety.~
@1404 = ~Part of me agrees with you, though I do not like to admit it. Cages, cages, always cages. No creature should have to suffer them, no matter how terrible they may be.~
@1405 = ~In truth, I know not why my mother dragged me into the Blood War as she did. Most of the time she seemed utterly disinterested in me, and when she did turn her gaze my direction, there was no scorn or hatred in her eyes. In some ways, I have wondered if perhaps she believed she was helping me by bringing me into the conflict.~
@1406 = ~Helping you how?~
@1407 = ~That's absurd, Haer'Dalis.~
@1408 = ~Maybe she wanted you to be part of the family business. Uh, so to speak.~
@1409 = ~You gained strength in the Blood War. She did you a favor.~
@1410 = ~Just looking at you had to have reminded her of the things your father did to her. I'm surprised she didn't kill you.~
@1411 = ~I do not know. Part demon I may be, but I do not claim to understand the inner workings of their thoughts. It was merely the impression I was given as my mother and I served our master.~
@1412 = ~Is it? Perhaps you are right, my raven. Regardless, it was a very long time ago and matters little in the present.~
@1413 = ~Actually, that is a fairly accurate summation of my impression as well. She seemed to think that joining the Blood War was inevitable for me, but that under her tutelage I might make something of myself. How odd to speak that thought out loud...~
@1414 = ~I do not disagree with you, but there are many ways to grow stronger. I'd have chosen another way to gain that same knowledge if I'd been given a choice.~
@1415 = ~When I freed her from my father's cage, for a moment I thought she would do just that. Even starved and tortured as she was, she could have easily crushed the weak child trembling at her feet. But she told me to run instead.~
@1416 = ~And with that, I believe I've had all I can tolerate of this particular topic. Come, my curious friend. Let us go.~
@1417 = ~Many reasons, my raven. Perhaps it is simplest to say that it was time for this sparrow to move on.~
@1418 = ~What other reasons did you have?~
@1419 = ~She didn't make much fuss over your departure.~
@1420 = ~Do you miss her?~
@1421 = ~Were you lovers?~
@1422 = ~I'm surprised she didn't ask you to leave after you botched the gem theft so badly.~
@1423 = ~Well, 'tis likely obvious that I was curious of you, my loyal rescuer. Perhaps I felt I owed you a debt of gratitude. I was also eager to experience the Prime Material Plane through more than the dim glimpses I caught from inside the playhouse walls.~
@1424 = ~I'm glad you stayed.~
@1425 = ~You tore yourself away from the life you knew and abandoned your companions out of simple curiosity?~
@1426 = ~Were you and Raelis lovers?~
@1427 = ~As am I, my dear <CHARNAME>.~
@1428 = ~My curiosity is rarely simple, but your assertion is not untrue. 'Tis far from the first time I've uprooted on a whim, and it will not be the last, I daresay.~
@1429 = ~No, that would not be her way, and even if it were, she knows me well enough to realize that no amount of theatrics would have swayed me.~
@1430 = ~So, she knew you'd leave sooner or later.~
@1431 = ~That she did. As a planewalker herself, she perfectly understands the urge to wander and does not blame me for it.~
@1432 = ~'Parting is such sweet sorrow.' I do, my raven, though truly I think of her with fondness and not with longing. I count myself fortunate to have known her.~
@1433 = ~I'd rather you not think of her at all...~
@1434 = ~Oh, my darling raven, jealousy looks utterly ravishing on you! Let me remind you that it was *you* who began this particular conversation. But there is no need to raise your hackles, I assure you. You have my full and undivided attention. Most of the time.~
@1435 = ~That *is* a rather personal question, now isn't it? I'm surprised at you, my raven!~
@1436 = ~I'd just rather you not think about her. At all.~
@1437 = ~Don't play coy! Give me the details!~
@1438 = ~I'm just curious.~
@1439 = ~I apologize if I've offended.~
@1440 = ~No, you aren't.~
@1441 = ~Fine, don't answer.~
@1442 = ~You are one nosy little gossipmonger, aren't you?~
@1443 = ~No need for that, my raven. I had hoped that my teasing would reveal that you are in fact jealous of my former mistress, thereby feeding my starving ego, but alas that you did not rise to the bait.~
@1444 = ~No, I suppose I am not. You've called my bluff.~
@1445 = ~Miss Raelis and I were indeed lovers from time to time, and as you saw firsthand, we parted amicably. There is really nothing more to it.~
@1446 = ~Why do you ask? Surely you cannot be jealous.~
@1447 = ~Maybe I just don't want you thinking about her.~
@1448 = ~Of course I'm jealous! I don't want to think about you with someone else!~
@1449 = ~I'm a little jealous, but mostly I'm just curious.~
@1450 = ~She's in your past, so I don't see what reason I'd have to be jealous.~
@1451 = ~I'm just trying to figure you out.~
@1452 = ~You are absolutely correct, my dear <CHARNAME>. Though your jealousy would surely feed my poor, undernourished ego, don't you think?~
@1453 = ~Oh-ho! Many have tried, and failed. I am eager to see if you fair better than the rest, my raven.~
@1454 = ~Why do you ask? 'Tis not as though I still carry on with her whilst dallying with you.~
@1455 = ~I freely admit that I'm a hypocrite. I'm jealous, Haer'Dalis! And she's not even here to be jealous of!~
@1456 = ~I... that is to say...~
@1457 = ~It's curiosity, not jealousy.~
@1458 = ~I have no idea what you're trying to imply.~
@1459 = ~Say nothing, my hound. There is no need to babble.~
@1460 = ~Ah, I see. If that is how you wish it, then so it shall be.~
@1461 = ~You think so? Miss Raelis appreciated the risks I took upon myself, even if events did not always go as planned.~
@1462 = ~I don't want to think about how she might have shown her appreciation to you...~
@1463 = ~I'm glad you chose to stay.~
@1464 = ~Perhaps you're right.~
@1465 = ~I only appreciate risks if they're accompanied by rewards.~
@1466 = ~I cannot disagree with that, my hound.~
@1467 = ~I hesitate to say this aloud because I do not wish it to be true, but I fear the spark within Miss Raelis which had for a time so thoroughly captivated me was fading away. Where once brazen courage and mad chaos danced behind her eyes, all this sparrow could see in the end was fear.~
@1468 = ~Considering what was chasing all of you, I can't blame her.~
@1469 = ~You weren't at all afraid? Even after being locked in that prison?~
@1470 = ~Perhaps she was wise for that. A life of recklessness tends to be a short one.~
@1471 = ~That kind of life can drag even the strongest person down.~
@1472 = ~She was weak to give in to fear.~
@1473 = ~No, I don't suppose I can blame her either. Although it was a mess she created, so I doubt anyone but Raelis is truly responsible for all that followed.~
@1474 = ~Well, that's hardly fair. Aye, this sparrow was indeed fearful to find himself in that place, and I am not ashamed to admit it.~
@1475 = ~I cannot deny that there is some wisdom in that.~
@1476 = ~You may be right, though I certainly hope you are not. I cannot comprehend how it is better to cower in the shadows and live than it is to stand in the sun and die.~
@1477 = ~It pains me to admit that your words echo my thoughts.~
@1478 = ~But this fear I speak of in Miss Raelis, it is not the sort of momentary, fleeting emotion that waxes and wanes from circumstance to circumstance. No, what I saw in her was... terror, constant and consuming. Where once she lived each day as it came, caught up in the mad whirl of the planes, now she clings to her life with the desperation of a drowning man.~
@1479 = ~This bard will never live like that.~
@1480 = ~Ah, but surely we've exhausted this topic. I find myself eager to fill my mind with something, anything else.~
@1481 = ~Why do you ask, my dear <CHARNAME>?~
@1482 = ~Sometimes I see you staring off at nothing at all, and I wonder what's on your mind.~
@1483 = ~I miss Candlekeep, and I thought it might be the same for you.~
@1484 = ~You seem homesick.~
@1485 = ~I want to make sure you're focused and not letting yourself get distracted.~
@1486 = ~Ah. I apologize. This sparrow did not realize he was wearing his heart on his sleeve, as it were.~
@1487 = ~Oh, I would not take it so far as all that.~
@1488 = ~Worry not, my hound. Your bard is ready, eager and unburdened by hapless longings. Lead on.~
@1489 = ~I cannot deny that I long for the city of my birth. A planewalker I am, and a planewalker I shall ever be, but The Bird Cage is and always will be *home* to this wandering bard. Though she knows I cannot tarry overlong in her arms, the embrace of my sweet Sigil waits for me.~
@1490 = ~But I do not dwell on it, raven. Either I will live to see her again or I will not.~
@1491 = ~That's a healthy attitude.~
@1492 = ~You move on so easily.~
@1493 = ~Sometimes I wonder if you care about anything or anyone.~
@1494 = ~Most likely the latter.~
@1495 = ~I'd like to think so, aye.~
@1496 = ~I would not say it is always easy, my raven, but I have lived long enough to be confident in my approach to life's ever changing terrain. 'Tis far better than the alternatives.~
@1497 = ~I admire your strength. I wish I could take life in stride the way you do.~
@1498 = ~Alternatives?~
@1499 = ~More of your nonsense? I think I've reached the limit of my tolerance for your rambling today, bard.~
@1500 = ~That's cold. Sometimes I wonder if you care about anything or anyone.~
@1501 = ~If you say so.~
@1502 = ~I was not always thus, <CHARNAME>. There was a time when this sparrow allowed attachments to temporary things to shape his world. It never ended well, but had I not endured those experiences, I would likely never have realized just how foolish I was.~
@1503 = ~Aye. Bitterness and madness are common enough, but the worst of all ways to face life is the one most often seen.~
@1504 = ~Stagnation.~
@1505 = ~Complacency.~
@1506 = ~'Tis a form of living death, my raven, that a man could be content to do nothing at all.~
@1507 = ~You have a healthy attitude.~
@1508 = ~What a coincidence, my hound, for at this very moment I've reached the limit of my tolerance for your moody snarling.~
@1509 = ~Do you indeed? That is unfortunate. There is likely no proper way to respond to such a statement, so let us away.~
@1510 = ~Ah, but now you've filled this bard's mind with desires long ignored! Quickly, my raven, use your talents to find my blades an enemy and drown my thoughts in battle!~
@1511 = ~There is nothing 'supposed' about it, my raven.~
@1512 = ~Then where is it?~
@1513 = ~Is that why there's parchment practically bursting from your pack?~
@1514 = ~I don't see you writing all that often.~
@1515 = ~I think you're full of rubbish. Let me see it.~
@1516 = ~Is your journey over, then? Are you ready to declare your story completed?~
@1517 = ~Well, no... I just...~
@1518 = ~Of course it isn't.~
@1519 = ~It will be soon.~
@1520 = ~Oh, don't be like this! I just want to see it.~
@1521 = ~Fine. Be stubborn.~
@1522 = ~I've never claimed to be organized. Or tidy.~
@1523 = ~Then you should pay more attention.~
@1524 = ~I assure you, my <CHARNAME>, I have done, and will continue to do for as long as I have breath, just as I claimed I would long ago. But your tale has not run its course, not by any stretch of the imagination. Be patient.~
@1525 = ~What? Never! A true artist does not go about flashing his unfinished creations for anyone to see, the subject itself least of all.~
@1526 = ~That was a bit dramatic, don't you think?~
@1527 = ~Did you just call me 'it?'~
@1528 = ~See! You *are* full of rubbish!~
@1529 = ~Not really, no.~
@1530 = ~Tsk, don't pick apart my melodramatic ravings.~
@1531 = ~I do indeed.~
@1532 = ~Aye, my raven, 'tis a grim turn, is it not?~
@1533 = ~Grim? The bastard betrayed us!~
@1534 = ~How could he have done something like this to me?~
@1535 = ~Grim, yes, but I think I feel sorry for him.~
@1536 = ~He had no choice, though that does not make it hurt any less.~
@1537 = ~I knew I couldn't trust him.~
@1538 = ~If only I could bring him back to life and kill him all over again!~
@1539 = ~'Twas no fault of your own, that much is clear. His path was set long before your paths crossed, it seems.~
@1540 = ~'Tis a rare person who can sympathize with their betrayer. He chose his side long ago, and 'twas a poor choice indeed, but still I think I understand what you mean. How things might have been different, had he known what was to come.~
@1541 = ~I wonder, does knowing now that one of your own could smile and lead you into the face of such pain and torment worry you at all?~
@1542 = ~You knew he was up to something, didn't you?~
@1543 = ~It does worry me. Who can I trust, Haer'Dalis, if not those who fight at my side?~
@1544 = ~A little, but I cannot let the actions of one man sway my entire way of thinking.~
@1545 = ~Not really. He was under a geas, after all, one made long before we'd ever met.~
@1546 = ~Nothing worries me. I am skilled enough to escape any foolish attempts at betrayal.~
@1547 = ~Glad I am to hear you say so. I would not wish for bitterness and suspicion to take you over.~
@1548 = ~I would doubt such bravdo and think you a fool, but seeing what you've overcome thus far makes me wonder.~
@1549 = ~Have faith, my raven, that all will be as it should, and know that this sparrow will never betray your company. I am here, as long as you have need of me.~
@1550 = ~How can I be sure of that? It could be that you knew Yoshimo was up to something.~
@1551 = ~Thank you, my sparrow, for lifting my spirits when I most need it.~
@1552 = ~I suppose I'll just have to take your word for it.~
@1553 = ~'As it should be' is often not the same as 'as I want it to be,' and that is not a pleasant thought.~
@1554 = ~All life exists to die, right Haer'Dalis? Your philosphy doesn't exactly inspire hope.~
@1555 = ~I have no need of your comfort. Let's get moving.~
@1556 = ~You are most welcome, my dear one.~
@1557 = ~I am pleased you accept my word, and pleased to be in your company 'till entropy catches me up.~
@1558 = ~Ah, but you've become quite skilled at adjusting to less than desirable outcomes, have you not? You will make do, I am certain.~
@1559 = ~'Tis only as hopeless as you wish to see it, my dear friend. Death is not the end, and opens the way for life and renewal. Surely there is hope in that, aye?~
@1560 = ~If I did know something of his motivations, how would you feel?~
@1561 = ~Gods above... you *knew*!~
@1562 = ~I would feel betrayed all over again.~
@1563 = ~It would break my heart.~
@1564 = ~I don't know. I suppose you'd have to be more specific.~
@1565 = ~I'm sure you'd have your reasons for not warning me.~
@1566 = ~I would feel like tearing your head from your shoulders!~
@1567 = ~And we would not want that, would we my fair raven? Come, we've delayed long enough.~
@1568 = ~Let us pretend, hypothetically of course, that your sparrow could sense the geas upon our dear departed blood hound's heart. Would my silence on this subject alarm you?~
@1569 = ~Enough word games! You *knew*.~
@1570 = ~I'd certainly say it would!~
@1571 = ~Yes, it would, so let's speak no more of it and move on.~
@1572 = ~I don't want to talk about this anymore. Let's just go.~
@1573 = ~I wouldn't be able to trust you anymore.~
@1574 = ~Please, Haer'Dalis, just be honest with me.~
@1575 = ~Would it alarm *you* to know that if I find your 'hypothetical' situation is true, I would strike you dead where you stand?~
@1576 = ~Aye, that I did.~
@1577 = ~And you said nothing? Why?~
@1578 = ~You... you bastard!~
@1579 = ~How could you betray me like this?~
@1580 = ~I thought you cared about me...~
@1581 = ~I'm not surprised.~
@1582 = ~I should kill you were you stand!~
@1583 = ~As did I.~
@1584 = ~I implore you, my dark hound, give me but a moment to explain!~
@1585 = ~My dear <CHARNAME>, you must believe that I adore you beyond my wildest expectations. If you would but let me explain.~
@1586 = ~The truth is, this sparrow could feel the shackles of sorcery upon our dear departed blood hound's soul. 'Tis something I've more experience with than I care to dwell upon, in fact. Truly, though, I did not know he was conspired with your mage tormentor.~
@1587 = ~Why didn't you say anything? You could have warned me, and I'd have thrown him from our company!~
@1588 = ~You were a fool not to tell me! Things could have been different if I'd but known!~
@1589 = ~I don't believe you. I think you knew more!~
@1590 = ~If you had known he was partnered with Irenicus, would you have told me?~
@1591 = ~That makes sense, I suppose. I still wish you'd said something sooner.~
@1592 = ~I believe you, and I understand.~
@1593 = ~Get away from me, you damned fool! You've proven yourself unworthy of me!~
@1594 = ~Aye, though I do not believe things would have turned out any differently.~
@1595 = ~For what it's worth, my dear one, I am pleased we escaped with our lives, and I will do everything in my power to avenge what was stolen from you while I yet draw breath.~
@1596 = ~I... <CHARNAME>... if that is your wish, then I shall obey. Forgive me.~
@1597 = ~What can I say to convince you, my raven?~
@1598 = ~Say that you love me.~
@1599 = ~Promise you will keep no more lies from me.~
@1600 = ~I... don't know. I think I just need time.~
@1601 = ~Nothing. Let's just move on and forget about this.~
@1602 = ~There is nothing to be said, so just get away from me! I want nothing more to do with you!~
@1603 = ~Is this the sort of affection you desire, my hound? Adoration confessed under duress, and you unable to be sure if it is truth or a prettily painted lie?~
@1604 = ~I don't care if it's not true! I just need comfort, so say it already!~
@1605 = ~I think you do love me and are just afraid to admit it.~
@1606 = ~I don't know what I want anymore, Haer'Dalis. Everything is such a mess.~
@1607 = ~No, it's not what I want. Forgive me.~
@1608 = ~Would you believe me if I spoke such words?~
@1609 = ~Comfort can mean so very many things, but even this actor cannot be all things at all times to all people. I cannot give you what you demand, and I am not sorry for that.~
@1610 = ~Then let your confidence be enough for now.~
@1611 = ~There is naught to forgive, I assure you, my raven.~
@1612 = ~Even had you known, can you truly say the outcome would have been different? You would still have sought Imoen and the foul mage Irenicus, with or without Yoshimo's influence, aye?~
@1613 = ~True. I could not leave Imoen to her fate.~
@1614 = ~I couldn't let Irenicus get away with all he's done, so I suppose you're right.~
@1615 = ~Maybe we'd have found another way. Maybe we'd have gotten here sooner and taken him by surprise.~
@1616 = ~What sort of stupid questions are these? No one can know what might have been!~
@1617 = ~You make excuses for yourself instead of offering regret!~
@1618 = ~I don't care! You kept vital information from me, and I cannot trust you! Get away from me, you fool!~
@1619 = ~Or maybe we'd have arrived too late. Maybe Imoen would have already been dead, and your mage long since departed. You cannot torment yourself with these thoughts, my raven.~
@1620 = ~If you believe that, then you surely realize how foolish it is to cling to resentment towards this sparrow. You have my confession, and I can offer you little more that I have not already sworn.~
@1621 = ~Would you have me pretend, then? To work up a false tear or two, to fall to my knees and beg pardon for my transgressions?~
@1622 = ~(sigh) I do not wish to fight, my raven.~
@1623 = ~Aye, she is a strong young woman to have survived that place alone. Her eyes are haunted, my raven, more so even than your own. 'Tis likely she has suffered worse atrocities than you realize whilst imprisoned.~
@1624 = ~Please don't make me think about that.~
@1625 = ~I know, and I wish I could do something to help her.~
@1626 = ~It should have been me! She was so innocent...~
@1627 = ~We all have our burdens to bear.~
@1628 = ~She needed to grow up. Now she has.~
@1629 = ~I don't care. All I wanted was Irenicus.~
@1630 = ~You have enough burdens, do you? No, you are right to silence this sparrow's song. 'Tis hard enough without digging the knife deeper, aye?~
@1631 = ~*Something*? My raven, you have done far, far more than *something* for that poor girl. If 'twere not for you, she would either be dead or still trapped in a fate worse than any death. Do not belittle your efforts.~
@1632 = ~Do not punish yourself with such foolish thoughts. Each of us walks our own road, and 'tis not for any berk to take the place of another.~
@1633 = ~Aye, you are wise to acknowledge that, and honest as well. If she is as strong as I suspect, then these terrible moments will do naught but buy her greater strength.~
@1634 = ~Mayhap 'tis so, and you would surely know better than this humble bard in this particular case. Still, your words smack of bitterness, my hound.~
@1635 = ~And that wanting has now turned to necessity and desperation, aye?~
@1636 = ~Tell me, what was your sister like before this? Is the change in her dramatic?~
@1637 = ~Is it ever! It's like looking at two different people.~
@1638 = ~She was a very silly child when we first left Candlekeep.~
@1639 = ~All of her charming innocence is gone.~
@1640 = ~Is it strange that it's hard to remember what she was like before?~
@1641 = ~I prefer this Imoen to the sniveling little brat she once was.~
@1642 = ~I never paid much attention to her.~
@1643 = ~'Tis a change nearly all living creatures must endure, these growing pains, though I doubt many can claim such literal pains as you and your kin have experienced. Does it sadden you, this change in her?~
@1644 = ~Very much. She didn't deserve all this, Haer'Dalis.~
@1645 = ~A little, but knowing now that she is a Child of Bhaal like myself, I wonder if this was unavoidable.~
@1646 = ~I'm trying not to think about it.~
@1647 = ~I have my own burdens to bear.~
@1648 = ~Are you kidding? It's about time she had to deal with something she can't just laugh off!~
@1649 = ~Life is never about what we deserve. You, my raven, should know that better than anyone.~
@1650 = ~Ah, a very intriguing notion. I like not the idea that anything might be unavoidable, but the lure of power such as moves through your blood is a mighty thing indeed. It seems unlikely that she might have avoided the Irenicuses of the realms forever.~
@1651 = ~Mayhap you should.~
@1652 = ~As do we all.~
@1653 = ~I have heard it said that those who laugh the loudest feel the most. Mayhap you have ever misunderstood the source of her mischief and lightness of heart.~
@1654 = ~Would others say the same of you?~
@1655 = ~Hah! Good point.~
@1656 = ~Definitely, though no one was as silly as Imoen.~
@1657 = ~Maybe I was a little silly. Once in a while.~
@1658 = ~I was a rather serious minded child, actually.~
@1659 = ~Absolutely not! Not if they wanted to keep all of their teeth in their head.~
@1660 = ~I couldn't possibly care less what they thought of me then, and I still don't care now.~
@1661 = ~We all began as something and someone else, aye?~
@1662 = ~I would have liked to know her then, I think, if only to witness this vast silliness you speak of.~
@1663 = ~This bard is relieved to hear that.~
@1664 = ~A pity, that. Childhood is the only time of life when such antics are not only tolerated, but expected and accepted.~
@1665 = ~Hah! And threats such as these are the mark of a mature and thoughtful youth, aye?~
@1666 = ~Methinks you ought learn to lie, my hound.~
@1667 = ~Perhaps not all, my raven. Given enough time, any wound can mend.~
@1668 = ~Perhaps not. Is it difficult to remember what *you* were like before your departure?~
@1669 = ~Yes. Nearly impossible, really.~
@1670 = ~Sometimes.~
@1671 = ~Not really difficult, no, but I don't let myself think about it.~
@1672 = ~Then I would say it is no great surprise that you cannot recall Imoen's former self either. I must admit, I would like nothing more than to see a single glimpse of the girl you once were. I would not wish you to be that girl again, for as you surely realize, I am decidedly fond of the woman you now are, but 'twould surely be a sight to behold.~
@1673 = ~I would never suggest anyone dwell upon the past, but that does not mean we should forget who we once were. Certainly not intentionally. Remember that, my raven.~
@1674 = ~Then I would say it is indeed a bit odd.~
@1675 = ~I wonder if she prefers this 'you' you have become to the 'you' you once were as well. I suppose it matters little either way. You are who you are.~
@1676 = ~I know not why, but that seems a pity to this humble bard.~
@1677 = ~This sparrow wonders, had you ever imagined Imoen could be a child of this Bhaal you call father?~
@1678 = ~Not even once, Haer'Dalis. It's still something I'm having a hard time accepting.~
@1679 = ~No, but maybe I should have. Maybe I just didn't want to see it.~
@1680 = ~I always wondered why she was brought to Candlekeep. I guess I know now.~
@1681 = ~There was always this weird feeling when I was near her, but I never made the connection.~
@1682 = ~Proof that the only thing in life that can be predicted is death, aye? Such a strange and curious twist in your tale, and in hers as well.~
@1683 = ~This does not seem the sort of thing that had many signs and portends attached to it, my raven, but 'tis true that the eye only sees what it wishes to see.~
@1684 = ~Aye, it makes one wonder just how much your fair monks knew of her. That sort of secrecy is such an odd beast in this sparrow's opinion.~
@1685 = ~How very interesting. I wonder if she felt the same.~
@1686 = ~Glad I am that you chose to bring the wayward wren with our company. She has as much at stake as you do, my dear raven.~
@1687 = ~It's my fault she ended up like this. I *had* to bring her.~
@1688 = ~We need each other, at least for now.~
@1689 = ~She's just taking up space until I find someone who's less of a liability.~
@1690 = ~No, she most certainly does not. Hers is the weaker soul, hence the reason Irenicus tossed it to his worthless sister and took mine instead. I have far more on the line than Imoen.~
@1691 = ~Quiet your guilt, fair raven, and let us work toward your goal instead.~
@1692 = ~Necessity is an interesting bedfellow, aye?~
@1693 = ~My hound, I can conjure a dozen reasons why any and all of us are liabilities. Including yourself! Mayhap you should not be so dismissive, aye?~
@1694 = ~Your estimation of yourself never ceases to awe this humble bard.~
@1695 = ~'Tis a pity she remained with us but for a short time. She has as much at stake as you do, my dear raven.~
@1696 = ~I wish I could have brought her with us, but... Oh, Haer'Dalis, I *should* have brought her with us!~
@1697 = ~She would have just gotten hurt more than she already is. This was necessary and for the best.~
@1698 = ~No, she would have been a liability.~
@1699 = ~Rumors and tall tales, aye, but stories of truth? Proof I have witnessed firsthand? No, my raven, I have not.~
@1700 = ~But it has to have happened before! I can't be the first one to survive something like this.~
@1701 = ~(Fight back the tears stinging your eyes.)~
@1702 = ~I see. I suppose I expected that answer. I just hoped that... (sigh) I don't know.~
@1703 = ~Then what good are you? What use is a bard who knows nothing?!~
@1704 = ~I will survive this. I will not allow Irenicus to succeed! That power is *mine*!~
@1705 = ~Technically speaking, Imoen survived it before you did, but I suppose that is not what you mean. You must realize that surviving the separation is not the same as *living* without a soul.~
@1706 = ~(sigh) My sweet <CHARNAME>...~
@1707 = ~(He pulls you into a tender embrace and presses gentle kisses against your temple as he holds you. Even so, his words are hard and commanding when next he speaks.)~
@1708 = ~You are stronger than this. Do not allow your soul-thief the satisfaction of this sort of victory. I take hope in this obvious indication that your emotions remain intact, but if you allow yourself to fall apart, I fear there will be no way to put you back together again afterward.~
@1709 = ~You hoped. My raven, that you hoped at all is a wondrous sign to this sparrow. If you can feel, if you have the ability to hope, then all is not lost. Take comfort in that as I do.~
@1710 = ~I understand your frustration, and normally I would be glad to accept your tongue lashing with all the grace this bard can muster. But... let us just say I fear your stability is not what it used to be. If you need to vent your anger, find an enemy to sink your claws into.~
@1711 = ~Then do not stop. Do not hesitate. Do not give up until he is ended.~
@1712 = ~I know of no other way to put this, so I shall simply say it. Without your soul, you will wither and die or... perhaps fall to some worse fate that I shall not put to voice. Regardless, you *must* retrieve that which is yours, or die trying.~
@1713 = ~I will not fail.~
@1714 = ~I know, Haer'Dalis. It's just hard to keep going sometimes.~
@1715 = ~Now that you've stated the obvious, can we go?~
@1716 = ~Save your foolish advice! You are here to kill those who cross me, not to lecture me on things I already know!~
@1717 = ~And you will not do it alone, my dear raven. Everything I am is at your disposal.~
@1718 = ~Speak no more of such things, and wipe them from your mind. Only one thing can come from such melancholy, and that is failure.~
@1719 = ~(Haer'Dalis catches your hand in his and briefly lifts it to his lips before gesturing for you to move on.)~
@1720 = ~Aye, that would be wise.~
@1721 = ~I am here for you, my hound, but I warn you that your temper is sure to lead to your downfall if you do not control it.~
@1722 = ~Similar in appearance, yes, in abundance. There are many even who are similar in function and behavior. The planes are filled with beasts beyond imagining, some mindless, some cunning, most somewhere betwixt the two. But these creatures are usually not capable of this fascinating shape-shift that o'ertakes you, and I have never felt in their presence what I feel in yours.~
@1723 = ~So, I'm unique?~
@1724 = ~What do you mean, how I make you feel?~
@1725 = ~I wonder how much control I have over it.~
@1726 = ~What else can you tell me about these monsters?~
@1727 = ~I cannot imagine being the Slayer or anything like it all the time. It would be unbearable!~
@1728 = ~That aura of yours I once mentioned to you long ago, do you remember? 'Tis an odd tingling behind my eyes when you are near, hot and angry and impossible to focus upon and yet equally impossible to ignore. It has always been there, but now...~
@1729 = ~'Tis o'erwhelming at times, my dear <CHARNAME>. This sparrow fears the rage inside you will smother and kill, though I know not if the victim will be your enemies, those who follow you, or you yourself. Mayhap all three?~
@1730 = ~Curious as I am, the memory of your clawed fingers seeking to tear holes in my lovely face has put a damper on my eagerness. If you do test your limits, be kind and give fair warning, aye?~
@1731 = ~Only what you already know, or can likely guess. They are deadly and dangerous, powerful and feared. Even so, they are also targets of stronger creatures. A beast such as your Slayer would make a fine prize pet in some Master's army, you see.~
@1732 = ~I am certain there are many other creatures who cannot imagine the horror of being a mere <PRO_RACE>, either.~
@1733 = ~I should of course mention that not one of the Slayer-like creatures I've seen was of divine parentage. This taint of Bhaal within you manifests itself in a way I fail to understand.~
@1734 = ~I... Forgive me, but I think 'twould be best to end this conversation. As strong as my curiosity is, I am haunted by a strange sense of foreboding each time we mention this beast within you. Come, let us move on. Please.~
@1735 = ~In truth? 'Twas spectacular, my raven. To find such a place here on the Prime was an unexpected delight to this sparrow, for many planewalkers search their entire lives to find a place with half as much intrigue and danger as the Underdark offers. If 'twere not for the urgency of your quest, I would have wished to linger there but a while longer.~
@1736 = ~Are you *crazy*?! The Underdark is horrible!~
@1737 = ~I suppose I should have expected you to say as much.~
@1738 = ~You can always visit it again someday.~
@1739 = ~It was fascinating, I agree.~
@1740 = ~Your loathing of the place is clear enough, but I do not understand the why of it. Tell me what *you* saw in the place, then.~
@1741 = ~Let's see... dark elves, mind flayers, beholders... With such charming denizens, what's not to love?~
@1742 = ~It was so oppressive. The darkness was so heavy, I felt like I could barely draw breath.~
@1743 = ~Between all the backstabbing, betrayal and manipulation, I don't know how anyone or anything survives down there.~
@1744 = ~My opinion is probably tainted by the circumstances that brought us there. In a different situation, maybe I'd be able to see it differently.~
@1745 = ~I was too focused on escaping to pay much attention.~
@1746 = ~Ah, my poor <CHARNAME>, in that darkness now behind us you saw only the barest glimpse of the sorts of creatures that exist across the planes. Mayhap that is why your frail planewalker sees it otherwise. Still, did you feel no desire to understand them? To spy their inner workings? To breathe in the essence of their culture?~
@1747 = ~A little, I admit.~
@1748 = ~Maybe, but I'm not sure curiosity is enough to override my other rather strong feelings about the place.~
@1749 = ~Not even a little bit, Haer'Dalis. Let the hells take the Underdark, and all within it!~
@1750 = ~Ah, this sparrow can sympathize with that feeling, aye. 'Tis the sort of nagging constant that increases in intensity the more one focuses upon it, or so I've found. But do you see nothing fascinating in the mere fact that such a place exists? 'Tis no cave or hole 'neath the ground - 'tis like unto a whole new Plane!~
@1751 = ~I never thought of it like that. I suppose it is a little interesting.~
@1752 = ~But they do more than survive - they *thrive*! Does that not fascinate you? Do you not long to explore their inner dealings until you understand them better than they understand themselves?~
@1753 = ~Perhaps, though I think this sparrow would prefer to involve personal opinion rather than ignore it, regardless of how it might prejudice a person. Mayhap another trip to the bowls of these lands is in order, once all this current madness is behind us?~
@1754 = ~It's possible, I suppose.~
@1755 = ~I don't know about that.~
@1756 = ~No, I don't think so.~
@1757 = ~Not a chance in the hells, Haer'Dalis!~
@1758 = ~A pity, that, my hound. Mayhap another trip to the bowls of these lands is in order, once all this current madness is behind us?~
@1759 = ~Do I imagine the disapproval in your tone?~
@1760 = ~No, I admire you. It takes amazing strength to see things as you do.~
@1761 = ~I like you just the way you are, my sparrow.~
@1762 = ~You do imagine it. I was just making an observation.~
@1763 = ~Hah! You hardly need my approval, do you?~
@1764 = ~You're always so infuriatingly *pleased* to be anywhere you happen to be. It's irritating!~
@1765 = ~Amazing strength, you say? Or amazing stubbornness, or amazing foolishness, aye? Hah! My raven you o'er flatter this humble Doomguard. 'Tis naught but childish curiosity that fascinates this bard at each passing locale. Do you feel nothing of that yourself? Did you truly pass through the Underdark and feel no fascination and longing to learn *more*?~
@1766 = ~I did. It was a truly wondrous place.~
@1767 = ~And I am ever glad for that, my sweet raven. I know not how anyone could pass through such a grand place as the Underdark and feel no touch of longing to explore further, no sudden need to comprehend the whole of those who dwell there.~
@1768 = ~It was a truly wondrous place.~
@1769 = ~I admit, I felt a little of that.~
@1770 = ~I understand where you're coming from, but I'm not sure curiosity is enough to override my other rather strong feelings about the place.~
@1771 = ~Personally, I didn't feel that.~
@1772 = ~Have you gone mad, Haer'Dalis? Let the hells take the Underdark, and all within it!~
@1773 = ~I see. Forgive my assumption then, my raven. I know not how anyone could pass through such a grand place as the Underdark and feel no touch of longing to explore further, no sudden need to comprehend the whole of those who dwell there.~
@1774 = ~True, and true. Ah, you know me too well, my dearest <CHARNAME>. I know not how anyone could pass through such a grand place as the Underdark and feel no touch of longing to explore further, no sudden need to comprehend the whole of those who dwell there.~
@1775 = ~I cannot be other than what I am, my hound! 'Tis naught but childish curiosity that fascinates this bard at each passing locale. Do you feel nothing of that yourself? Did you truly pass through the Underdark and feel no fascination and longing to learn *more*?~
@1776 = ~Aye, I suppose I could at that. Would you return, if given the chance?~
@1777 = ~With you? Certainly.~
@1778 = ~I would indeed.~
@1779 = ~Perhaps, but not anytime soon.~
@1780 = ~Probably not.~
@1781 = ~If we should survive these events yet to come, mayhap we could return and see more of the splendor of this underground haven of darkness and shadow?~
@1782 = ~Well, 'tis good you have left it behind you, then. 'Twould be wise to guide your steps a bit more carefully if you should wish to avoid such places in the future, aye?~
@1783 = ~This sparrow would very much enjoy a return trip to the darkness below, one driven by less urgency and more curiosity. 'Twould be grand to have you at my side should that day come, my raven.~
@1784 = ~Aye, unfriendly and deceptive. Believe you me, my raven, that a liar knows a liar. Our fair Elhan is as untruthful a berk as ever I've seen.~
@1785 = ~What makes you say that?~
@1786 = ~He must have good reason for his behavior.~
@1787 = ~Delays, and yet more delays...~
@1788 = ~We have no choice but to trust him for now.~
@1789 = ~Fool bastard *will* get out of my way if he knows what's good for him!~
@1790 = ~Aside from the evasive speeches and forced inquisition into our associations? My raven, surely you jest. The elf could not have made his act any more obvious had he worn a straw wig and read from a poor wrought script!~
@1791 = ~Aye, perhaps, though 'tis likely that his good reasons are not in our best interest. Let us hope this sparrow is wrong on that.~
@1792 = ~You are right to be impatient, my hound. To have hope that at long last we shall truly catch your mage-thief up, only to be forestalled by embittered elves...~
@1793 = ~There is always a choice. 'Tis fair to say our course is best served by serving this elf for the moment, but I shall leave the trusting to you, for I trust not myself with the task.~
@1794 = ~One way or another, aye?~
@1795 = ~'Tis rather enlightening, truth be told. My dear father would have everyone believe that Tel'Quessir are the picture of beauty, honesty and flawless perfection. There is a strange satisfaction comes o'er this sparrow now that I see 'tis otherwise.~
@1796 = ~The People are not always at their best, you know. Perhaps you should not judge this Elhan too harshly, Haer'Dalis, nor should you cast aspersions upon all Tel'Quessir simply to spite your father.~
@1797 = ~I have never understood the arrogance of my fellow elves. It only weakens them and makes them look like greater fools.~
@1798 = ~Perhaps it's because I'm only half-elven, but I have never understood the arrogance of my fellow elves. It only weakens them and makes them look like greater fools.~
@1799 = ~I don't pretend to understand the nature of all elves, but perhaps you should not judge this Elhan too harshly, Haer'Dalis.~
@1800 = ~Elves prove their arrogance and ignorance at every turn. That they could not even hold this Lanthorn of theirs is proof of their ineptitude!~
@1801 = ~I can understand how that might be satisfying.~
@1802 = ~Careful, Haer'Dalis. Your bitterness is showing.~
@1803 = ~I apologize, my raven. 'Twas thoughtless of me to speak ill of those you might very well count as kin. If it is any consolation, I do not think of you as some extension of Tel'Quessir - I think of you as <CHARNAME>.~
@1804 = ~Aye, this sparrow has come to realize that the true downfall of the elves lies in their own pride. Mayhap 'tis unwise to speak ill of those who might well be our allies, but on occasion, truth cannot be ignored.~
@1805 = ~Perhaps not. 'Tis unfair to speak ill of those we might well call ally soon enough.~
@1806 = ~Then this sparrow is not completely mad? 'Tis good to know, my fair <CHARNAME>.~
@1807 = ~Hah! Aye, it is, is it not? Mayhap this frail bard ought not expose himself so publicly, hmm?~
@1808 = ~Let us hope that we were not deceived on this bargain, at least. Should we return this Lanthorn of theirs and still find that our path to Irenicus blocked...~
@1809 = ~We won't. I have faith, Haer'Dalis.~
@1810 = ~Then we'll deal with that obstacle when it comes.~
@1811 = ~He will not escape again. No matter what it takes, he will *not* escape again.~
@1812 = ~Then someone will die. Lots of someones, most likely.~
@1813 = ~I refuse to entertain thoughts like that. Let's go.~
@1814 = ~(sigh) I know not whether to fear for you and the crushing disappointment that you will one day face, or whether I ought to fear for myself as I follow your faith so blindly.~
@1815 = ~One moment at a time, aye? Wise, my raven. Wiser than I at times.~
@1816 = ~If it is in this sparrow's power to make certain of that, then know you can call upon me.~
@1817 = ~If only murder were enough...~
@1818 = ~Has it brought you any satisfaction?~
@1819 = ~No. Irenicus remains.~
@1820 = ~Not really, but at least she got what she deserved.~
@1821 = ~I thought it would, but...~
@1822 = ~Satisfaction? No. Relief? A bit, yes.~
@1823 = ~Oh, undoubtedly, but this isn't over yet.~
@1824 = ~Hah! Did you see her face at the end? The fear, the disbelief! It was a wondrous thing to behold, wasn't it?~
@1825 = ~The mage will not escape our efforts forever, my raven.~
@1826 = ~Aye, would that all who wrong us get half as much.~
@1827 = ~It feels nothing like you expected? Aye, that is the truth of vengeance, and 'tis a cold comfort this sparrow knows well. There is naught that can be done but to accept it and move forward, my raven.~
@1828 = ~Because Imoen's soul is safely returned?~
@1829 = ~Yes.~
@1830 = ~That, and some selfish reasons as well.~
@1831 = ~I'm not entirely sure why I feel that way.~
@1832 = ~It means I'm one step closer to Irenicus.~
@1833 = ~If Bodhi can die, so can her brother.~
@1834 = ~The light returns to her eyes quickly. I hope to see the same in yours soon enough.~
@1835 = ~Why? Does her death give you hope that Irenicus can be defeated?~
@1836 = ~I'm just glad she doesn't have Imoen's soul anymore.~
@1837 = ~If she can die, so can her brother.~
@1838 = ~A pity the girl is not here with us. 'Twould be good to see her begin to return to being the girl you once knew instead of the hollow shell I first met.~
@1839 = ~Ah, my raven, my raven! Do remind me never to become your enemy, aye?~
@1840 = ~Do you truly believe Irenicus is within our grasp now? Or will he slip free once more, as he did in the aslyum, as he did in the Underdark?~
@1841 = ~He's not going to escape again.~
@1842 = ~I don't think he went to all this trouble just to run again. He's after something specific.~
@1843 = ~No matter how far he runs, I'll be right on his heels. He'll slip up eventually.~
@1844 = ~Damn it, Haer'Dalis, do you just want me to give up? Is that it?~
@1845 = ~Keep moving, and stop talking about things like this.~
@1846 = ~I hope you are correct.~
@1847 = ~Aye, this sparrow feels it, too.~
@1848 = ~My hound, how long can you keep hunting? How long until your sanity is crushed 'neath the weight of your soulless existence? This cannot carry on.~
@1849 = ~If that were my wish, I would say nothing, my fierce hound. I would stand aside and watch as you fall to pieces, and I would revel in the entropy of your fate.~
@1850 = ~You must be prepared for the possibility that you will not succeed. *I* must be prepared for that possibility, though it is--~
@1851 = ~Ah, come, we ought not delay, aye?~
@1852 = ~What were you going to say?~
@1853 = ~Is it really so hard to tell me you care?~
@1854 = ~(sigh) Let's just go.~
@1855 = ~Coward.~
@1856 = ~Either shut your mouth, or stop holding back!~
@1857 = ~Must I truly put voice to my worries? Would it be any comfort to add my fears and doubts to your own? No, my raven, ask me not for such things.~
@1858 = ~Oh. Well. Great.~
@1859 = ~What, no doom and entropy and death to add to that?~
@1860 = ~I assume you expected me to have a different reply.~
@1861 = ~Must I truly state the obvious, my raven?~
@1862 = ~You asked if we can win. To that there is only one reply - we *can*. There is always that possibility. Now, *will* we? I know not, my raven. Truly, I know not.~
@1863 = ~You sound troubled.~
@1864 = ~I suppose any chance is better than none.~
@1865 = ~We won't fail. I won't let us fail.~
@1866 = ~Do you think we're prepared, at least?~
@1867 = ~I don't know what I was thinking, looking to you for encouragement.~
@1868 = ~Right. Let's just get to it.~
@1869 = ~That is perhaps not the best word for what I feel, but it shall suffice. I am anxious to know the conclusion of this drama, and that feeling alone is... odd. I revel with equal fervor in both the journey and the destination, yet I find the thought that further delays may yet keep us from Irenicus to be frustrating and pointless.~
@1870 = ~I want your soul returned to you. I want to look once more into your eyes and see <CHARNAME> gazing back at me.~
@1871 = ~No more shall we wait. Go, my raven. Lead us to your fate.~
@1872 = ~'Twas not luck that carried us thus far, my raven. You are no mere child who needs be told their value. Your skills and abilities speak for themselves. Let them now speak to this Irenicus in a voice both loud and bold, and we shall see what is to come of all this you have suffered.~
@1873 = ~(Haer'Dalis catches your hand in his and lifts your knuckles to his lips for a slow, lingering kiss. Turning his eyes up to watch your reaction, he then turns your hand over and kisses the sensitive pulse point of your wrist as well.)~
@1874 = ~This bard would happily encourage you in so very many ways, my sweet <CHARNAME>, but time is not our friend at this moment. You soul waits for you, but how long will it wait? Let us delay no more. Onward.~
@1875 = ~(Haer'Dalis catches you up in his arms and kisses your lips with all the urgency and need of a dying man. After a wild moment of passion, his touch softens and his lips shift to pressing gentle murmuring brushes across your cheeks, your chin, your nose, your forehead.)~
@1876 = ~I could not possibly agree more, my raven. Whilst this sparrow loves the road and all the adventure and danger it brings, it could certainly do to be less filthy.~
@1877 = ~I'm having a bath brought up to my room. Why don't you join me? I'll wash your back, you wash mine...~
@1878 = ~You should have a tub brought up to your room. And you should invite me to join you.~
@1879 = ~Enjoy yourself while we have the time.~
@1880 = ~I fully intend to. Rest well, <CHARNAME>.~
@1881 = ~You as well, <CHARNAME>.~
@1882 = ~A most intriguing offer. This sparrow wonders if you mean to tease him, or if your desires are honest.~
@1883 = ~Perfectly honest. Interested?~
@1884 = ~Are you willing to find out?~
@1885 = ~Desires are never honest, mine least of all. But in this I know what I want.~
@1886 = ~No, I suppose it's not a good idea. Rest well, Haer'Dalis.~
@1887 = ~I jest, my friend. Enjoy your rest.~
@1888 = ~I should? And why is that? So you may wash this sparrow's feet?~
@1889 = ~Feet, knees, elbows... and anywhere else you want me to touch.~
@1890 = ~Precisely. I have a devious foot fetish.~
@1891 = ~My sparrow, I want you naked, I want you wet, and I want you alone.~
@1892 = ~If you're going to play coy, forget I said anything.~
@1893 = ~Ah, never mind. Enjoy your rest.~
@1894 = ~Very much so.~
@1895 = ~I would be a fool to let this chance pass me by, my raven.~
@1896 = ~You must know how much pleasure it brings this sparrow to hear you wax philosophical whilst expressing your longing for me.~
@1897 = ~Hah! Whether or not you jest, I cannot deny I find you all the more intriguing for such a declaration. What other secret longings hide in your heart?~
@1898 = ~Ah, a woman who knows exactly what she wants and does not fear saying so. 'Tis a splendid vision that stands before me.~
@1899 = ~Hold! Tsk, you've no sense of humor, my surly friend.~
@1900 = ~What would my raven say if I were to pay for a bath big enough for two? Would she be inclined to accept such a proposition?~
@1901 = ~I was the one who propositioned you, wasn't I?~
@1902 = ~She would.~
@1903 = ~Hurry yourself, tiefling, before I change my mind.~
@1904 = ~I'm not sure. Convince me that this is something I want.~
@1905 = ~On second thought, perhaps this isn't the best idea.~
@1906 = ~You began this game, my dear. Should not *you* be doing the persuading?~
@1907 = ~I suppose it's too late to play hard to get, isn't it?~
@1908 = ~Oh? What then must I do to persuade you, hmm?~
@1909 = ~Tsk, must a girl beg for a kiss?~
@1910 = ~Oh, I would say that it is indeed.~
@1911 = ~Very well. Call for that bath-built-for-two.~
@1912 = ~This filthy raven would very much enjoy your company as she grooms herself, sparrow. Is that plain enough for you?~
@1913 = ~Perhaps not. Rest well, fair raven.~
@1914 = ~Oh, my dear <CHARNAME>, you cannot imagine what your teasing is doing to this poor helpless sparrow...~
@1915 = ~The thought of you on your knees, begging for *anything* is an idea I would give much to see become reality.~
@1916 = ~Give me but a handful of heartbeats to make arrangements. I shall shortly return to fetch you.~
@1917 = ~I'll just have a drink while I wait.~
@1918 = ~Perfect.~
@1919 = ~Don't take too long.~
@1920 = ~(Haer'Dalis takes your hand and flashes you a warm smile, then bows with a flourish and presses a quick kiss against your knuckles before disappearing into the crowd.)~
@1921 = ~(Order a drink while you wait for him.)~
@1922 = ~(Wait patiently.)~
@1923 = ~(Tap your foot impatiently as you wait.)~
@1924 = ~(Decide this is probably a bad idea and slip off to your room.)~
@1925 = ~(When he returns a few moments later, Haer'Dalis raises a playful eyebrow at your drink.)~
@1926 = ~Seeking a taste or two of liquid courage, are you?~
@1927 = ~Judging by the color of your cheeks, you've indulged a bit as well.~
@1928 = ~I'm just relaxing a little.~
@1929 = ~What else am I supposed to do when I'm bored?~
@1930 = ~Ready?~
@1931 = ~I have indeed, oh perceptive one. It isn't everyday that a half-goddess invites me to bathe with her.~
@1932 = ~Play your cards right and it just might become an everyday occurrence.~
@1933 = ~Please don't put me on a pedestal...~
@1934 = ~Let's see if you're up to the challenge, shall we?~
@1935 = ~A challenge I readily accept.~
@1936 = ~I meant to tease you only, my raven. I cannot deny that I desire you, but I long for you because you are <CHARNAME> and for no other reason.~
@1937 = ~Come, take my arm. Your bath awaits.~
@1938 = ~(Silently take his arm.)~
@1939 = ~It's about time.~
@1940 = ~(Slide past him to lead the way to his room, letting your hips sway in silent invitation with each step.)~
@1941 = ~I know better ways to ease your tension, my dear <CHARNAME>.~
@1942 = ~Many ideas come to mind...~
@1943 = ~(Haer'Dalis returns a moment later and offers you his arm.)~
@1944 = ~Your bath awaits, my raven.~
@1945 = ~(When he returns, Haer'Dalis laughs and offers you his arm.)~
@1946 = ~Come, my eager raven. Your bath awaits.~
@1947 = ~Some things cannot be rushed, I fear.~
@1948 = ~(The bard curls his fingers over yours and guides the pair of you toward his room. The hallway is empty when you reach his door, and instead of opening it he twists quickly to press your back against the hard wood.)~
@1949 = ~(Haer'Dalis hums low in his throat in appreciation. You can hear him following at a short distance behind you, but in the empty hallway outside his room, he slips an arm around your waist and twists quickly to press your back against the hard wood.)~
@1950 = ~(The door creaks under the pressure as Haer'Dalis pins you with his body, his hands moving to cradle your face as he murmurs something about 'irresistible' and 'lips.' His eyes flicker over your features for a moment before he leans down to kiss you.)~
@1951 = ~(Meet his lips eagerly.)~
@1952 = ~(Let him kiss you.)~
@1953 = ~Nuh-uh, not so fast.~
@1954 = ~Wait!~
@1955 = ~(Push him roughly away.)~
@1956 = ~(The door creaks under the pressure as Haer'Dalis drops to one knee and pins you with his body, his hands moving to cradle your face as he murmurs something about 'irresistible' and 'lips.' His eyes flicker over your features for a moment before he leans down to kiss you.)~
@1957 = ~(Soft, full lips capture your mouth in a longing and insistent kiss. You breathe in the faint scent of wine and brimstone as the tiefling pulls you closer, his arms strong and solid around your waist as he deepens the kiss. His tongue teases across your lower lip and you can feel the growl in his chest rumble through you, leaving your mouth tingling. Restless fingers caress along your jawline and the edge of your ear, then slide into your hair, as if he wants to memorize you with his touch.)~
@1958 = ~(The need for air forces you apart, but Haer'Dalis smiles wryly and rests his forehead against yours.)~
@1959 = ~I am loathe to shatter this moment with logic, but I fear I must ask you to answer me plainly. This sparrow is a lover of games and manipulation alike, but in this I need a plain answer from you.~
@1960 = ~My raven, if you enter this room, you and I will be doing far more than bathing, and I have no intention of letting you leave for several hours at least. And you will likely need another bath by the time we finish. In fact, I guarantee it.~
@1961 = ~If this is not what you wish from me, speak now. I will not hold it against you should you choose to excuse yourself.~
@1962 = ~Are you mad? What did you think I wanted when I asked to share a bath with you?~
@1963 = ~Several hours, you say? Prove it.~
@1964 = ~All I wanted was a bath.~
@1965 = ~This was a mistake.~
@1966 = ~(The bard draws in a sharp breath through his nose, then throws himself into the kiss with obvious relief. His hands skim up your hips and waist, eager to touch and learn your body.)~
@1967 = ~I... Well, it does make me sound rather stupid when you put it that way, but I wanted no misunderstanding, you see? Bah, since you don't seem inclined to do it for me, I will shut my own mouth with a kiss.~
@1968 = ~(And he does, his lips and tongue mapping the contours of your mouth as his hands skim up your hips and waist, eager to touch and learn your body.)~
@1969 = ~That is my intention.~
@1970 = ~(He dips to kiss you again, his lips and tongue mapping the contours of your mouth as his hands skim up your hips and waist, eager to touch and learn your body.)~
@1971 = ~I see. Then I must insist you have a bath brought to your own room. If you will excuse me, my raven.~
@1972 = ~I am disappointed, of course, but glad that you realized it before things had gone any farther. If you will excuse me, my raven.~
@1973 = ~(Soft, full lips capture your mouth in a longing and insistent kiss. You breathe in the faint scent of wine and brimstone as the tiefling pulls you closer, his arms strong and solid around you as he deepens the kiss. When he realizes that you are mostly unresponsive, he pulls away with a puzzled look written across his face.)~
@1974 = ~(The bard groans in protest, but obediently eases his hold on you and leans back to meet your eyes.)~
@1975 = ~Is something wrong, <CHARNAME>?~
@1976 = ~Yes. We're not in the bath yet.~
@1977 = ~No, I'm just eager for that bath.~
@1978 = ~I think there's a misunderstanding. I'm here for a *bath*.~
@1979 = ~Wait. There is something that must be made clear first.~
@1980 = ~(Clearly unprepared to be shoved, Haer'Dalis staggers backward and hits the far wall where he stands blinking at you in surprise and confusion.)~
@1981 = ~<CHARNAME>...? Have I misunderstood?~
@1982 = ~(Lunge at him and kiss him fiercely.)~
@1983 = ~Oh, I didn't mean to push you so hard! It's just... I want that bath...~
@1984 = ~You don't touch me without permission. Ever. Is that clear?~
@1985 = ~(Haer'Dalis practically snarls into your mouth as he returns the violent kiss that is all teeth and tongues. His battle-hardened hands grip your hips with bruising force, but before either of you can lose yourself in the wave of passion, it is his turn to push you away. Panting, he regards you with dark, heated eyes.)~
@1986 = ~(Haer'Dalis narrows his eyes at you in calculation before slowly approaching to stand but a hairsbreadth from you. His gaze never leaves yours.)~
@1987 = ~Will you permit me to touch you, my deadly half-goddess?~
@1988 = ~Why should I?~
@1989 = ~(Somehow Haer'Dalis manages to get the door open and maneuver the pair of you into his room, kicking the door shut with enough force to crack the frame. You break apart long enough to discover that there is indeed a large tub filled with steaming water in the corner of the room.)~
@1990 = ~(Ignore the bath and turn back to the bard.)~
@1991 = ~So... you wash my back, I'll wash yours?~
@1992 = ~Undress me, my sparrow.~
@1993 = ~Well? Take those clothes off, bard.~
@1994 = ~This was a very bad idea. I have to go.~
@1995 = ~No, no my raven. Bath first! I must insist. We are both rather... putrid.~
@1996 = ~I am *not* putrid!~
@1997 = ~My raven, you are enticing, desirable and utterly intoxicating... but you are also filthy and you reek of the road.~
@1998 = ~I will gladly wash your back, your front, and anything else you wish me to thoroughly clean, my raven.~
@1999 = ~(While distracting you with breathless kisses and nibbles and exploratory touches, Haer'Dalis' nimble fingers make short work of your clothing. When at last your body is bare to his sight, he takes a step back from you, hungry eyes roving over every curve, every muscle, every scar, drinking you in with his gaze.)~
@2000 = ~Well, this is hardly fair.~
@2001 = ~Are you done memorizing me?~
@2002 = ~(Tap your foot impatiently.)~
@2003 = ~I do. You cannot possibly imagine how much.~
@2004 = ~No. Perhaps I never will be.~
@2005 = ~(Haer'Dalis laughs and shakes his head, his eyes sparkling with warmth.)~
@2006 = ~(While distracting you with breathless kisses and touches and the nearness of his bare skin, Haer'Dalis' nimble fingers make short work of your clothing. When at last your body is bare to his sight, he takes a step back from you, hungry eyes roving over every curve, every muscle, every scar, drinking you in with his gaze.)~
@2007 = ~(Silently allow him to admire you.)~
@2008 = ~Breathtaking.~
@2009 = ~(Without a word, Haer'Dalis slowly begins to strip away his own garments, his eyes fixed on your face. Once nude, he stands unashamed before you.)~
@2010 = ~You're positively shameless.~
@2011 = ~I know.~
@2012 = ~(Lean, feline muscles cover the tiefling's frame, his olive skin littered with scars and tattoos. What look to be claw marks pucker the flesh of his left breast, as if someone or something tried to tear his heart from his chest. A scaly green serpent tattoo circles his entire torso, twisting over his ribs and around his lower back. Etched on his stomach, its snarling jaws are clamped around its own tail.)~
@2013 = ~(A faint trail of silver-blue hair wanders between his abs and lower, the color only a few shades darker than the hair on his head. His desire for you is obvious, and the tiefling seems perfectly at ease under your scrutiny.)~
@2014 = ~Such a beautiful tattoo.~
@2015 = ~(Touch the deep scar on his chest.)~
@2016 = ~(The tiefling busies himself with removing your clothes, pausing occasionally to whisper kisses across your bare shoulders.)~
@2017 = ~(Turn toward the bath.)~
@2018 = ~It is beautiful and full of truth. Yet I have eyes only for you, <CHARNAME>.~
@2019 = ~(With a grim smile, he catches your hand and kisses your palm.) The appetites of some women are quite literal. I nearly met my end that day, but it seems this sparrow does not taste as good as he looks.~
@2020 = ~But I wonder... do you?~
@2021 = ~(Haer'Dalis moves away from you, his gaze thoughtful but guarded. After a pause, he gestures toward the door and turns away from you.)~
@2022 = ~(Without preamble, the tiefling ushers you into the bath, moving slowly and carefully to keep as much of the water from sloshing over the side as possible. It is a snug fit with the both of you in the tub, but Haer'Dalis immediately sets to work with a cake of soap and a soft wash rag.)~
@2023 = ~(His hands follow the lines of your body, easing away not just the dirt and grime of the road, but any lingering tension and discomfort your lifestyle brings you. There is tenderness beneath the lust in the bard's touch, and it is an easy thing to lose yourself in the sensations of the moment.)~
@2024 = ~(So caught up in learning each other, neither of you notice that the water has gone cold.)~
